properties.description: The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: list description
properties.description: Creating an amazon issued certificate

properties.name: domain_name
properties.description: (Required) A domain name for which the certificate should be issued

properties.name: subject_alternative_names
properties.description: (Optional) A list of domains that should be SANs in the issued certificate

properties.name: validation_method
properties.description: (Required) Which method to use for validation. DNS or EMAIL are valid, NONE can be used for certificates that were imported into ACM and then into Terraform.

properties.name: list description
properties.description: Importing an existing certificate

properties.name: private_key
properties.description: (Required) The certificate's PEM-formatted private key

properties.name: certificate_body
properties.description: (Required) The certificate's PEM-formatted public key

properties.name: certificate_chain
properties.description: (Optional) The certificate's PEM-formatted chain

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: certificate_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the certificate that is being validated.

properties.name: validation_record_fqdns
properties.description: (Optional) List of FQDNs that implement the validation. Only valid for DNS validation method ACM certificates. If this is set, the resource can implement additional sanity checks and has an explicit dependency on the resource that is implementing the validation
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: certificate_authority_configuration
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument containing algorithms and certificate subject information. Defined below.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the certificate authority is enabled or disabled. Defaults to true.

properties.name: revocation_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument containing revocation configuration. Defined below.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies a key-value map of user-defined tags that are attached to the certificate authority.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of the certificate authority. Defaults to SUBORDINATE. Valid values: ROOT and SUBORDINATE.

properties.name: permanent_deletion_time_in_days
properties.description: (Optional) The number of days to make a CA restorable after it has been deleted, must be between 7 to 30 days, with default to 30 days.

properties.name: certificate_authority_configuration-1
properties.description: » certificate_authority_configuration

properties.name: key_algorithm
properties.description: (Required) Type of the public key algorithm and size, in bits, of the key pair that your key pair creates when it issues a certificate. Valid values can be found in the ACM PCA Documentation.

properties.name: signing_algorithm
properties.description: (Required) Name of the algorithm your private CA uses to sign certificate requests. Valid values can be found in the ACM PCA Documentation.

properties.name: subject
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that contains X.500 distinguished name information. At least one nested attribute must be specified.

properties.name: subject-1
properties.description: » subject
Contains information about the certificate subject. Identifies the entity that owns or controls the public key in the certificate. The entity can be a user, computer, device, or service.

properties.name: common_name
properties.description: (Optional) Fully qualified domain name (FQDN) associated with the certificate subject.

properties.name: country
properties.description: (Optional) Two digit code that specifies the country in which the certificate subject located.

properties.name: distinguished_name_qualifier
properties.description: (Optional) Disambiguating information for the certificate subject.

properties.name: generation_qualifier
properties.description: (Optional) Typically a qualifier appended to the name of an individual. Examples include Jr. for junior, Sr. for senior, and III for third.

properties.name: given_name
properties.description: (Optional) First name.

properties.name: initials
properties.description: (Optional) Concatenation that typically contains the first letter of the given_name, the first letter of the middle name if one exists, and the first letter of the surname.

properties.name: locality
properties.description: (Optional) The locality (such as a city or town) in which the certificate subject is located.

properties.name: organization
properties.description: (Optional) Legal name of the organization with which the certificate subject is affiliated.

properties.name: organizational_unit
properties.description: (Optional) A subdivision or unit of the organization (such as sales or finance) with which the certificate subject is affiliated.

properties.name: pseudonym
properties.description: (Optional) Typically a shortened version of a longer given_name. For example, Jonathan is often shortened to John. Elizabeth is often shortened to Beth, Liz, or Eliza.

properties.name: state
properties.description: (Optional) State in which the subject of the certificate is located.

properties.name: surname
properties.description: (Optional) Family name. In the US and the UK for example, the surname of an individual is ordered last. In Asian cultures the surname is typically ordered first.

properties.name: title
properties.description: (Optional) A title such as Mr. or Ms. which is pre-pended to the name to refer formally to the certificate subject.

properties.name: revocation_configuration-1
properties.description: » revocation_configuration

properties.name: crl_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument containing configuration of the certificate revocation list (CRL), if any, maintained by the certificate authority. Defined below.

properties.name: crl_configuration-1
properties.description: » crl_configuration

properties.name: custom_cname
properties.description: (Optional) Name inserted into the certificate CRL Distribution Points extension that enables the use of an alias for the CRL distribution point. Use this value if you don't want the name of your S3 bucket to be public.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Boolean value that specifies whether certificate revocation lists (CRLs) are enabled. Defaults to false.

properties.name: expiration_in_days
properties.description: (Required) Number of days until a certificate expires. Must be between 1 and 5000.

properties.name: s3_bucket_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the S3 bucket that contains the CRL. If you do not provide a value for the custom_cname argument, the name of your S3 bucket is placed into the CRL Distribution Points extension of the issued certificate. You must specify a bucket policy that allows ACM PCA to write the CRL to your bucket.
The following argument is supported:

properties.name: cloudwatch_role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of an IAM role for CloudWatch (to allow logging & monitoring). See more in AWS Docs. Logging & monitoring can be enabled/disabled and otherwise tuned on the API Gateway Stage level.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the API key

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The API key description. Defaults to "Managed by Terraform".

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the API key can be used by callers. Defaults to true.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Optional) The value of the API key. If not specified, it will be automatically generated by AWS on creation.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: authorizer_uri
properties.description: (Optional, required for type TOKEN/REQUEST) The authorizer's Uniform Resource Identifier (URI). This must be a well-formed Lambda function URI in the form of arn:aws:apigateway:{region}:lambda:path/{service_api}, e.g. arn:aws:apigateway:us-west-2:lambda:path/2015-03-31/functions/arn:aws:lambda:us-west-2:012345678912:function:my-function/invocations

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the authorizer

properties.name: rest_api_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the associated REST API

properties.name: identity_source
properties.description: (Optional) The source of the identity in an incoming request. Defaults to method.request.header.Authorization. For REQUEST type, this may be a comma-separated list of values, including headers, query string parameters and stage variables

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of the authorizer. Possible values are TOKEN for a Lambda function using a single authorization token submitted in a custom header, REQUEST for a Lambda function using incoming request parameters, or COGNITO_USER_POOLS for using an Amazon Cognito user pool. Defaults to TOKEN.

properties.name: authorizer_credentials
properties.description: (Optional) The credentials required for the authorizer. To specify an IAM Role for API Gateway to assume, use the IAM Role ARN.

properties.name: authorizer_result_ttl_in_seconds
properties.description: (Optional) The TTL of cached authorizer results in seconds. Defaults to 300.

properties.name: identity_validation_expression
properties.description: (Optional) A validation expression for the incoming identity. For TOKEN type, this value should be a regular expression. The incoming token from the client is matched against this expression, and will proceed if the token matches. If the token doesn't match, the client receives a 401 Unauthorized response.

properties.name: provider_arns
properties.description: (Optional, required for type COGNITO_USER_POOLS) A list of the Amazon Cognito user pool ARNs. Each element is of this format: arn:aws:cognito-idp:{region}:{account_id}:userpool/{user_pool_id}.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: domain_name
properties.description: (Required) The already-registered domain name to connect the API to.

properties.name: api_id
properties.description: (Required) The id of the API to connect.

properties.name: stage_name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of a specific deployment stage to expose at the given path. If omitted, callers may select any stage by including its name as a path element after the base path.

properties.name: base_path
properties.description: (Optional) Path segment that must be prepended to the path when accessing the API via this mapping. If omitted, the API is exposed at the root of the given domain.

When referencing an AWS-managed certificate, the following arguments are supported:

properties.name: certificate_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for an AWS-managed certificate. AWS Certificate Manager is the only supported source. Used when an edge-optimized domain name is desired. Conflicts with certificate_name, certificate_body, certificate_chain, certificate_private_key, regional_certificate_arn, and regional_certificate_name.

properties.name: regional_certificate_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for an AWS-managed certificate. AWS Certificate Manager is the only supported source. Used when a regional domain name is desired. Conflicts with certificate_arn, certificate_name, certificate_body, certificate_chain, and certificate_private_key.
When uploading a certificate, the following arguments are supported:

properties.name: certificate_name
properties.description: (Optional) The unique name to use when registering this certificate as an IAM server certificate. Conflicts with certificate_arn, regional_certificate_arn, and regional_certificate_name. Required if certificate_arn is not set.

properties.name: certificate_body
properties.description: (Optional) The certificate issued for the domain name being registered, in PEM format. Only valid for EDGE endpoint configuration type. Conflicts with certificate_arn, regional_certificate_arn, and regional_certificate_name.

properties.name: certificate_chain
properties.description: (Optional) The certificate for the CA that issued the certificate, along with any intermediate CA certificates required to create an unbroken chain to a certificate trusted by the intended API clients. Only valid for EDGE endpoint configuration type. Conflicts with certificate_arn, regional_certificate_arn, and regional_certificate_name.

properties.name: certificate_private_key
properties.description: (Optional) The private key associated with the domain certificate given in certificate_body. Only valid for EDGE endpoint configuration type. Conflicts with certificate_arn, regional_certificate_arn, and regional_certificate_name.

properties.name: regional_certificate_name
properties.description: (Optional) The user-friendly name of the certificate that will be used by regional endpoint for this domain name. Conflicts with certificate_arn, certificate_name, certificate_body, certificate_chain, and certificate_private_key.

properties.name: types
properties.description: (Required) A list of endpoint types. This resource currently only supports managing a single value. Valid values: EDGE or REGIONAL. If unspecified, defaults to EDGE. Must be declared as REGIONAL in non-Commercial partitions. Refer to the documentation for more information on the difference between edge-optimized and regional APIs.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: rest_api_id
properties.description: (Required) The string identifier of the associated REST API.

properties.name: response_type

properties.name: status_code
properties.description: (Optional) The HTTP status code of the Gateway Response.

properties.name: response_parameters
properties.description: (Optional) A map specifying the templates used to transform the response body.

properties.name: response_templates
properties.description: (Optional) A map specifying the parameters (paths, query strings and headers) of the Gateway Response.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: rest_api_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the associated REST API.

properties.name: resource_id
properties.description: (Required) The API resource ID.

properties.name: http_method
properties.description: (Required) The HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, HEAD, OPTION, ANY) when calling the associated resource.

properties.name: integration_http_method
properties.description: (Optional) The integration HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONs, ANY, PATCH) specifying how API Gateway will interact with the back end. Required if type is AWS, AWS_PROXY, HTTP or HTTP_PROXY. Not all methods are compatible with all AWS integrations. e.g. Lambda function can only be invoked via POST.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The integration input's type. Valid values are HTTP (for HTTP backends), MOCK (not calling any real backend), AWS (for AWS services), AWS_PROXY (for Lambda proxy integration) and HTTP_PROXY (for HTTP proxy integration). An HTTP or HTTP_PROXY integration with a connection_type of VPC_LINK is referred to as a private integration and uses a VpcLink to connect API Gateway to a network load balancer of a VPC.

properties.name: connection_type
properties.description: (Optional) The integration input's connectionType. Valid values are INTERNET (default for connections through the public routable internet), and VPC_LINK (for private connections between API Gateway and a network load balancer in a VPC).

properties.name: connection_id
properties.description: (Optional) The id of the VpcLink used for the integration. Required if connection_type is VPC_LINK

properties.name: uri
properties.description: (Optional) The input's URI. Required if type is AWS, AWS_PROXY, HTTP or HTTP_PROXY. For HTTP integrations, the URI must be a fully formed, encoded HTTP(S) URL according to the RFC-3986 specification . For AWS integrations, the URI should be of the form arn:aws:apigateway:{region}:{subdomain.service|service}:{path|action}/{service_api}. region, subdomain and service are used to determine the right endpoint. e.g. arn:aws:apigateway:eu-west-1:lambda:path/2015-03-31/functions/arn:aws:lambda:eu-west-1:012345678901:function:my-func/invocations

properties.name: credentials
properties.description: (Optional) The credentials required for the integration. For AWS integrations, 2 options are available. To specify an IAM Role for Amazon API Gateway to assume, use the role's ARN. To require that the caller's identity be passed through from the request, specify the string arn:aws:iam::\*:user/\*.

properties.name: request_templates
properties.description: (Optional) A map of the integration's request templates.

properties.name: request_parameters
properties.description: (Optional) A map of request query string parameters and headers that should be passed to the backend responder. For example: request_parameters = { "integration.request.header.X-Some-Other-Header" = "method.request.header.X-Some-Header" }

properties.name: passthrough_behavior
properties.description: (Optional) The integration passthrough behavior (WHEN_NO_MATCH, WHEN_NO_TEMPLATES, NEVER). Required if request_templates is used.

properties.name: cache_key_parameters
properties.description: (Optional) A list of cache key parameters for the integration.

properties.name: cache_namespace
properties.description: (Optional) The integration's cache namespace.

properties.name: content_handling
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies how to handle request payload content type conversions. Supported values are CONVERT_TO_BINARY and CONVERT_TO_TEXT. If this property is not defined, the request payload will be passed through from the method request to integration request without modification, provided that the passthroughBehaviors is configured to support payload pass-through.

properties.name: timeout_milliseconds
properties.description: (Optional) Custom timeout between 50 and 29,000 milliseconds. The default value is 29,000 milliseconds.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: rest_api_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the associated REST API

properties.name: resource_id
properties.description: (Required) The API resource ID

properties.name: http_method
properties.description: (Required) The HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONS, ANY)

properties.name: status_code
properties.description: (Required) The HTTP status code

properties.name: selection_pattern
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the regular expression pattern used to choose an integration response based on the response from the backend. Setting this to - makes the integration the default one. If the backend is an AWS Lambda function, the AWS Lambda function error header is matched. For all other HTTP and AWS backends, the HTTP status code is matched.

properties.name: response_templates
properties.description: (Optional) A map specifying the templates used to transform the integration response body

properties.name: response_parameters
properties.description: (Optional) A map of response parameters that can be read from the backend response. For example: response_parameters = { "method.response.header.X-Some-Header" = "integration.response.header.X-Some-Other-Header" }

properties.name: content_handling
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies how to handle request payload content type conversions. Supported values are CONVERT_TO_BINARY and CONVERT_TO_TEXT. If this property is not defined, the response payload will be passed through from the integration response to the method response without modification.

properties.description: (Required) - API Id of the associated API stage in a usage plan.

properties.description: » Quota Settings Arguments

properties.name: limit
properties.description: (Optional) - The maximum number of requests that can be made in a given time period.

properties.name: offset
properties.description: (Optional) - The number of requests subtracted from the given limit in the initial time period.

properties.name: period
properties.description: (Optional) - The time period in which the limit applies. Valid values are "DAY", "WEEK" or "MONTH".

properties.name: throttling-settings-arguments
properties.description: » Throttling Settings Arguments

properties.name: burst_limit
properties.description: (Optional) - The API request burst limit, the maximum rate limit over a time ranging from one to a few seconds, depending upon whether the underlying token bucket is at its full capacity.

properties.name: nested-fields
properties.description: » Nested fields

properties.name: step_scaling_policy_configuration-1
properties.description: » step_scaling_policy_configuration

properties.name: adjustment_type
properties.description: (Required) Specifies whether the adjustment is an absolute number or a percentage of the current capacity. Valid values are ChangeInCapacity, ExactCapacity, and PercentChangeInCapacity.

properties.name: cooldown
properties.description: (Required) The amount of time, in seconds, after a scaling activity completes and before the next scaling activity can start.

properties.name: metric_aggregation_type
properties.description: (Optional) The aggregation type for the policy's metrics. Valid values are "Minimum", "Maximum", and "Average". Without a value, AWS will treat the aggregation type as "Average".

properties.name: min_adjustment_magnitude
properties.description: (Optional) The minimum number to adjust your scalable dimension as a result of a scaling activity. If the adjustment type is PercentChangeInCapacity, the scaling policy changes the scalable dimension of the scalable target by this amount.

properties.name: step_adjustment
properties.description: (Optional) A set of adjustments that manage scaling. These have the following structure:

resource "aws_appautoscaling_policy" "ecs_policy" {
  # ...

  step_scaling_policy_configuration {
    # insert config here

    step_adjustment {
      metric_interval_lower_bound = 1.0
      metric_interval_upper_bound = 2.0
      scaling_adjustment          = -1
    }

    step_adjustment {
      metric_interval_lower_bound = 2.0
      metric_interval_upper_bound = 3.0
      scaling_adjustment          = 1
    }
  }
}

properties.name: metric_interval_lower_bound
properties.description: (Optional) The lower bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric. Without a value, AWS will treat this bound as negative infinity.

properties.name: metric_interval_upper_bound
properties.description: (Optional) The upper bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric. Without a value, AWS will treat this bound as infinity. The upper bound must be greater than the lower bound.

properties.name: scaling_adjustment
properties.description: (Required) The number of members by which to scale, when the adjustment bounds are breached. A positive value scales up. A negative value scales down.

properties.name: target_tracking_scaling_policy_configuration-1
properties.description: » target_tracking_scaling_policy_configuration

properties.name: target_value
properties.description: (Required) The target value for the metric.

properties.name: disable_scale_in
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether scale in by the target tracking policy is disabled. If the value is true, scale in is disabled and the target tracking policy won't remove capacity from the scalable resource. Otherwise, scale in is enabled and the target tracking policy can remove capacity from the scalable resource. The default value is false.

properties.name: scale_in_cooldown
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time, in seconds, after a scale in activity completes before another scale in activity can start.

properties.name: scale_out_cooldown
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time, in seconds, after a scale out activity completes before another scale out activity can start.
