properties.description: (Optional) The number of Amazon EC2 instances that should be running in the group. (See also Waiting for Capacity below.)

properties.name: force_delete
properties.description: (Optional) Allows deleting the autoscaling group without waiting for all instances in the pool to terminate. You can force an autoscaling group to delete even if it's in the process of scaling a resource. Normally, Terraform drains all the instances before deleting the group. This bypasses that behavior and potentially leaves resources dangling.

properties.name: load_balancers
properties.description: (Optional) A list of elastic load balancer names to add to the autoscaling group names. Only valid for classic load balancers. For ALBs, use target_group_arns instead.

properties.name: vpc_zone_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) A list of subnet IDs to launch resources in.

properties.name: target_group_arns
properties.description: (Optional) A list of aws_alb_target_group ARNs, for use with Application or Network Load Balancing.

properties.name: termination_policies
properties.description: (Optional) A list of policies to decide how the instances in the auto scale group should be terminated. The allowed values are OldestInstance, NewestInstance, OldestLaunchConfiguration, ClosestToNextInstanceHour, OldestLaunchTemplate, AllocationStrategy, Default.

properties.name: suspended_processes
properties.description: (Optional) A list of processes to suspend for the AutoScaling Group. The allowed values are Launch, Terminate, HealthCheck, ReplaceUnhealthy, AZRebalance, AlarmNotification, ScheduledActions, AddToLoadBalancer. Note that if you suspend either the Launch or Terminate process types, it can prevent your autoscaling group from functioning properly.

properties.name: tag
properties.description: (Optional) A list of tag blocks. Tags documented below.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A list of tag blocks (maps). Tags documented below.

properties.name: placement_group
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the placement group into which you'll launch your instances, if any.

properties.name: metrics_granularity
properties.description: (Optional) The granularity to associate with the metrics to collect. The only valid value is 1Minute. Default is 1Minute.

properties.name: enabled_metrics
properties.description: (Optional) A list of metrics to collect. The allowed values are GroupMinSize, GroupMaxSize, GroupDesiredCapacity, GroupInServiceInstances, GroupPendingInstances, GroupStandbyInstances, GroupTerminatingInstances, GroupTotalInstances.

properties.name: wait_for_capacity_timeout
properties.description: (Default: "10m") A maximum duration that Terraform should wait for ASG instances to be healthy before timing out. (See also Waiting for Capacity below.) Setting this to "0" causes Terraform to skip all Capacity Waiting behavior.

properties.name: min_elb_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) Setting this causes Terraform to wait for this number of instances from this autoscaling group to show up healthy in the ELB only on creation. Updates will not wait on ELB instance number changes. (See also Waiting for Capacity below.)

properties.name: wait_for_elb_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) Setting this will cause Terraform to wait for exactly this number of healthy instances from this autoscaling group in all attached load balancers on both create and update operations. (Takes precedence over min_elb_capacity behavior.) (See also Waiting for Capacity below.)

properties.name: protect_from_scale_in
properties.description: (Optional) Allows setting instance protection. The autoscaling group will not select instances with this setting for terminination during scale in events.

properties.name: service_linked_role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the service-linked role that the ASG will use to call other AWS services

properties.name: launch_template-1
properties.description: » launch_template
NOTE: Either id or name must be specified.
The top-level launch_template block supports the following:

properties.name: id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the launch template. Conflicts with name.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the launch template. Conflicts with id.

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Optional) Template version. Can be version number, $Latest, or $Default. (Default: $Default).

properties.name: mixed_instances_policy-1
properties.description: » mixed_instances_policy

properties.name: instances_distribution
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument containing settings on how to mix on-demand and Spot instances in the Auto Scaling group. Defined below.

properties.name: launch_template
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument containing launch template settings along with the overrides to specify multiple instance types. Defined below.

properties.name: mixed_instances_policy-instances_distribution
properties.description: » mixed_instances_policy instances_distribution
This configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: on_demand_allocation_strategy
properties.description: (Optional) Strategy to use when launching on-demand instances. Valid values: prioritized. Default: prioritized.

properties.name: on_demand_base_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) Absolute minimum amount of desired capacity that must be fulfilled by on-demand instances. Default: 0.

properties.name: on_demand_percentage_above_base_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) Percentage split between on-demand and Spot instances above the base on-demand capacity. Default: 100.

properties.name: spot_allocation_strategy
properties.description: (Optional) How to allocate capacity across the Spot pools. Valid values: lowest-price. Default: lowest-price.

properties.name: spot_instance_pools
properties.description: (Optional) Number of Spot pools per availability zone to allocate capacity. EC2 Auto Scaling selects the cheapest Spot pools and evenly allocates Spot capacity across the number of Spot pools that you specify. Default: 2.

properties.name: spot_max_price
properties.description: (Optional) Maximum price per unit hour that the user is willing to pay for the Spot instances. Default: an empty string which means the on-demand price.

properties.name: mixed_instances_policy-launch_template
properties.description: » mixed_instances_policy launch_template
This configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: launch_template_specification
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument defines the Launch Template. Defined below.

properties.name: override
properties.description: (Optional) List of nested arguments provides the ability to specify multiple instance types. This will override the same parameter in the launch template. For on-demand instances, Auto Scaling considers the order of preference of instance types to launch based on the order specified in the overrides list. Defined below.

properties.name: mixed_instances_policy-launch_template-launch_template_specification
properties.description: » mixed_instances_policy launch_template launch_template_specification
NOTE: Either launch_template_id or launch_template_name must be specified.
This configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: launch_template_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the launch template. Conflicts with launch_template_name.

properties.name: launch_template_name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the launch template. Conflicts with launch_template_id.

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Optional) Template version. Can be version number, $Latest, or $Default. (Default: $Default).

properties.name: mixed_instances_policy-launch_template-override
properties.description: » mixed_instances_policy launch_template override
This configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: instance_type
properties.description: (Optional) Override the instance type in the Launch Template.

properties.name: tag-and-tags
properties.description: » tag and tags
The tag attribute accepts exactly one tag declaration with the following fields:

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Required) Key

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) Value

properties.name: propagate_at_launch
properties.description: (Required) Enables propagation of the tag to Amazon EC2 instances launched via this ASG

To declare multiple tags additional tag blocks can be specified. Alternatively the tags attributes can be used, which accepts a list of maps containing the above field names as keys and their respective values. This allows the construction of dynamic lists of tags which is not possible using the single tag attribute. tag and tags are mutually exclusive, only one of them can be specified.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the lifecycle hook.

properties.name: autoscaling_group_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the Auto Scaling group to which you want to assign the lifecycle hook

properties.name: default_result
properties.description: (Optional) Defines the action the Auto Scaling group should take when the lifecycle hook timeout elapses or if an unexpected failure occurs. The value for this parameter can be either CONTINUE or ABANDON. The default value for this parameter is ABANDON.

properties.name: heartbeat_timeout
properties.description: (Optional) Defines the amount of time, in seconds, that can elapse before the lifecycle hook times out. When the lifecycle hook times out, Auto Scaling performs the action defined in the DefaultResult parameter

properties.name: lifecycle_transition
properties.description: (Required) The instance state to which you want to attach the lifecycle hook. For a list of lifecycle hook types, see describe-lifecycle-hook-types

properties.name: notification_metadata
properties.description: (Optional) Contains additional information that you want to include any time Auto Scaling sends a message to the notification target.

properties.name: notification_target_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the notification target that Auto Scaling will use to notify you when an instance is in the transition state for the lifecycle hook. This ARN target can be either an SQS queue or an SNS topic.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the IAM role that allows the Auto Scaling group to publish to the specified notification target.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: group_names
properties.description: (Required) A list of AutoScaling Group Names

properties.name: notifications
properties.description: (Required) A list of Notification Types that trigger notifications. Acceptable values are documented in the AWS documentation here

properties.name: topic_arn
properties.description: (Required) The Topic ARN for notifications to be sent through
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the policy.

properties.name: autoscaling_group_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the autoscaling group.

properties.name: adjustment_type
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the adjustment is an absolute number or a percentage of the current capacity. Valid values are ChangeInCapacity, ExactCapacity, and PercentChangeInCapacity.

properties.name: policy_type
properties.description: (Optional) The policy type, either "SimpleScaling", "StepScaling" or "TargetTrackingScaling". If this value isn't provided, AWS will default to "SimpleScaling."

properties.name: estimated_instance_warmup
properties.description: (Optional) The estimated time, in seconds, until a newly launched instance will contribute CloudWatch metrics. Without a value, AWS will default to the group's specified cooldown period.
The following arguments are only available to "SimpleScaling" type policies:

properties.name: cooldown
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time, in seconds, after a scaling activity completes and before the next scaling activity can start.

properties.name: scaling_adjustment
properties.description: (Optional) The number of instances by which to scale. adjustment_type determines the interpretation of this number (e.g., as an absolute number or as a percentage of the existing Auto Scaling group size). A positive increment adds to the current capacity and a negative value removes from the current capacity.
The following arguments are only available to "StepScaling" type policies:

properties.name: metric_aggregation_type
properties.description: (Optional) The aggregation type for the policy's metrics. Valid values are "Minimum", "Maximum", and "Average". Without a value, AWS will treat the aggregation type as "Average".

properties.name: step_adjustments
properties.description: (Optional) A set of adjustments that manage group scaling. These have the following structure:

step_adjustment {
  scaling_adjustment          = -1
  metric_interval_lower_bound = 1.0
  metric_interval_upper_bound = 2.0
}

step_adjustment {
  scaling_adjustment          = 1
  metric_interval_lower_bound = 2.0
  metric_interval_upper_bound = 3.0
}
The following fields are available in step adjustments:

properties.name: scaling_adjustment
properties.description: (Required) The number of members by which to scale, when the adjustment bounds are breached. A positive value scales up. A negative value scales down.

properties.name: metric_interval_lower_bound
properties.description: (Optional) The lower bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric. Without a value, AWS will treat this bound as infinity.

properties.name: metric_interval_upper_bound
properties.description: (Optional) The upper bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric. Without a value, AWS will treat this bound as infinity. The upper bound must be greater than the lower bound.
The following arguments are only available to "TargetTrackingScaling" type policies:

properties.name: target_tracking_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) A target tracking policy. These have the following structure:

target_tracking_configuration {
  predefined_metric_specification {
    predefined_metric_type = "ASGAverageCPUUtilization"
  }

  target_value = 40.0
}

target_tracking_configuration {
  customized_metric_specification {
    metric_dimension {
      name  = "fuga"
      value = "fuga"
    }

    metric_name = "hoge"
    namespace   = "hoge"
    statistic   = "Average"
  }

  target_value = 40.0
}
The following fields are available in target tracking configuration:

properties.name: predefined_metric_specification
properties.description: (Optional) A predefined metric. Conflicts with customized_metric_specification.

properties.name: customized_metric_specification
properties.description: (Optional) A customized metric. Conflicts with predefined_metric_specification.

properties.name: target_value
properties.description: (Required) The target value for the metric.

properties.name: disable_scale_in
properties.description: (Optional, Default: false) Indicates whether scale in by the target tracking policy is disabled.

properties.name: predefined_metric_specification-1
properties.description: » predefined_metric_specification
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: predefined_metric_type
properties.description: (Required) The metric type.

properties.name: resource_label
properties.description: (Optional) Identifies the resource associated with the metric type.

properties.name: customized_metric_specification-1
properties.description: » customized_metric_specification
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: metric_dimension
properties.description: (Optional) The dimensions of the metric.

properties.name: metric_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the metric.

properties.name: namespace
properties.description: (Required) The namespace of the metric.

properties.name: statistic
properties.description: (Required) The statistic of the metric.

properties.name: unit
properties.description: (Optional) The unit of the metric.

properties.name: metric_dimension-1
properties.description: » metric_dimension
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the dimension.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) The value of the dimension.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: autoscaling_group_name
properties.description: (Required) The name or Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Auto Scaling group.

properties.name: scheduled_action_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of this scaling action.

properties.name: start_time
properties.description: (Optional) The time for this action to start, in "YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssZ" format in UTC/GMT only (for example, 2014-06-01T00:00:00Z ). If you try to schedule your action in the past, Auto Scaling returns an error message.

properties.name: end_time
properties.description: (Optional) The time for this action to end, in "YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssZ" format in UTC/GMT only (for example, 2014-06-01T00:00:00Z ). If you try to schedule your action in the past, Auto Scaling returns an error message.

properties.name: recurrence
properties.description: (Optional) The time when recurring future actions will start. Start time is specified by the user following the Unix cron syntax format.

properties.name: min_size
properties.description: (Optional) The minimum size for the Auto Scaling group. Default 0. Set to -1 if you don't want to change the minimum size at the scheduled time.

properties.name: max_size
properties.description: (Optional) The maximum size for the Auto Scaling group. Default 0. Set to -1 if you don't want to change the maximum size at the scheduled time.

properties.name: desired_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) The number of EC2 instances that should be running in the group. Default 0. Set to -1 if you don't want to change the desired capacity at the scheduled time.
NOTE: When start_time and end_time are specified with recurrence , they form the boundaries of when the recurring action will start and stop.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The display name of a backup plan.

properties.name: rule
properties.description: (Required) A rule object that specifies a scheduled task that is used to back up a selection of resources.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Metadata that you can assign to help organize the plans you create.

properties.name: rule-arguments
properties.description: » Rule Arguments
For rule the following attributes are supported:

properties.name: rule_name
properties.description: (Required) An display name for a backup rule.

properties.name: target_vault_name
properties.description: (Required) - The name of a logical container where backups are stored.

properties.name: schedule
properties.description: (Optional) - A CRON expression specifying when AWS Backup initiates a backup job.

properties.name: start_window
properties.description: (Optional) - The amount of time in minutes before beginning a backup.

properties.name: completion_window
properties.description: (Optional) - The amount of time AWS Backup attempts a backup before canceling the job and returning an error.

properties.name: lifecycle
properties.description: (Optional) - The lifecycle defines when a protected resource is transitioned to cold storage and when it expires. Fields documented below.

properties.name: recovery_point_tags
properties.description: (Optional) - Metadata that you can assign to help organize the resources that you create.

properties.name: lifecycle-arguments
properties.description: » Lifecycle Arguments
For lifecycle the following attributes are supported:

properties.name: cold_storage_after
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the number of days after creation that a recovery point is moved to cold storage.

properties.name: delete_after
properties.description: (Optional) - Specifies the number of days after creation that a recovery point is deleted. Must be 90 days greater than cold_storage_after.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The display name of a resource selection document.

properties.name: plan_id
properties.description: (Required) The backup plan ID to be associated with the selection of resources.

properties.name: iam_role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the IAM role that AWS Backup uses to authenticate when restoring and backing up the target resource. See the AWS Backup Developer Guide for additional information about using AWS managed policies or creating custom policies attached to the IAM role.

properties.name: selection_tag
properties.description: (Optional) Tag-based conditions used to specify a set of resources to assign to a backup plan.

properties.name: resources
properties.description: (Optional) An array of strings that either contain Amazon Resource Names (ARNs) or match patterns of resources to assign to a backup plan..
Tag conditions (selection_tag) support the following:

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) An operation, such as StringEquals, that is applied to a key-value pair used to filter resources in a selection.

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Required) The key in a key-value pair.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) The value in a key-value pair.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Name of the backup vault to create.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Metadata that you can assign to help organize the resources that you create.

properties.name: kms_key_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The server-side encryption key that is used to protect your backups.

properties.name: compute_environment_name
properties.description: (Required) The name for your compute environment. Up to 128 letters (uppercase and lowercase), numbers, and underscores are allowed.

properties.name: compute_resources
properties.description: (Optional) Details of the compute resources managed by the compute environment. This parameter is required for managed compute environments. See details below.

properties.name: service_role
properties.description: (Required) The full Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role that allows AWS Batch to make calls to other AWS services on your behalf.

properties.name: state
properties.description: (Optional) The state of the compute environment. If the state is ENABLED, then the compute environment accepts jobs from a queue and can scale out automatically based on queues. Valid items are ENABLED or DISABLED. Defaults to ENABLED.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of the compute environment. Valid items are MANAGED or UNMANAGED.
compute_resources is a child block with a single argument:

properties.name: bid_percentage
properties.description: (Optional) Integer of minimum percentage that a Spot Instance price must be when compared with the On-Demand price for that instance type before instances are launched. For example, if your bid percentage is 20% (20), then the Spot price must be below 20% of the current On-Demand price for that EC2 instance. This parameter is required for SPOT compute environments.

properties.name: desired_vcpus
properties.description: (Optional) The desired number of EC2 vCPUS in the compute environment.

properties.name: ec2_key_pair
properties.description: (Optional) The EC2 key pair that is used for instances launched in the compute environment.

properties.name: image_id
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon Machine Image (AMI) ID used for instances launched in the compute environment.

properties.name: instance_role
properties.description: (Required) The Amazon ECS instance role applied to Amazon EC2 instances in a compute environment.

properties.name: instance_type
properties.description: (Required) A list of instance types that may be launched.

properties.name: launch_template
properties.description: (Optional) The launch template to use for your compute resources. See details below.

properties.name: max_vcpus
properties.description: (Required) The maximum number of EC2 vCPUs that an environment can reach.

properties.name: min_vcpus
properties.description: (Required) The minimum number of EC2 vCPUs that an environment should maintain.

properties.name: security_group_ids
properties.description: (Required) A list of EC2 security group that are associated with instances launched in the compute environment.

properties.name: spot_iam_fleet_role
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon EC2 Spot Fleet IAM role applied to a SPOT compute environment. This parameter is required for SPOT compute environments.

properties.name: subnets
properties.description: (Required) A list of VPC subnets into which the compute resources are launched.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value pair tags to be applied to resources that are launched in the compute environment.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of compute environment. Valid items are EC2 or SPOT.

properties.name: launch_template-1
properties.description: » launch_template
launch_template supports the following:

properties.name: launch_template_id
properties.description: (Optional) ID of the launch template. You must specify either the launch template ID or launch template name in the request, but not both.

properties.name: launch_template_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the launch template.

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Optional) The version number of the launch template. Default: The default version of the launch template.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the job definition.

properties.name: container_properties
properties.description: (Optional) A valid container properties provided as a single valid JSON document. This parameter is required if the type parameter is container.

properties.name: parameters
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the parameter substitution placeholders to set in the job definition.

properties.name: retry_strategy
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the retry strategy to use for failed jobs that are submitted with this job definition. Maximum number of retry_strategy is 1. Defined below.

properties.name: timeout
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the timeout for jobs so that if a job runs longer, AWS Batch terminates the job. Maximum number of timeout is 1. Defined below.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of job definition. Must be container

properties.name: retry_strategy-1
properties.description: » retry_strategy
retry_strategy supports the following:

properties.name: attempts
properties.description: (Optional) The number of times to move a job to the RUNNABLE status. You may specify between 1 and 10 attempts.

properties.name: timeout-1
properties.description: » timeout
timeout supports the following:

properties.name: attempt_duration_seconds
properties.description: (Optional) The time duration in seconds after which AWS Batch terminates your jobs if they have not finished. The minimum value for the timeout is 60 seconds.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the job queue.

properties.name: compute_environments
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the set of compute environments mapped to a job queue and their order. The position of the compute environments in the list will dictate the order. You can associate up to 3 compute environments with a job queue.

properties.name: priority
properties.description: (Required) The priority of the job queue. Job queues with a higher priority are evaluated first when associated with the same compute environment.

properties.name: state
properties.description: (Required) The state of the job queue. Must be one of: ENABLED or DISABLED
For more detailed documentation about each argument, refer to the AWS official documentation.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: account_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the target account for budget. Will use current user's account_id by default if omitted.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of a budget. Unique within accounts.

properties.name: name_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) The prefix of the name of a budget. Unique within accounts.

properties.name: budget_type
properties.description: (Required) Whether this budget tracks monetary cost or usage.

properties.name: cost_filters
properties.description: (Optional) Map of CostFilters key/value pairs to apply to the budget.

properties.name: cost_types
properties.description: (Optional) Object containing CostTypes The types of cost included in a budget, such as tax and subscriptions..

properties.name: limit_amount
properties.description: (Required) The amount of cost or usage being measured for a budget.

properties.name: limit_unit
properties.description: (Required) The unit of measurement used for the budget forecast, actual spend, or budget threshold, such as dollars or GB. See Spend documentation.

properties.name: time_period_end
properties.description: (Optional) The end of the time period covered by the budget. There are no restrictions on the end date. Format: 2017-01-01_12:00.

properties.name: time_period_start
properties.description: (Required) The start of the time period covered by the budget. The start date must come before the end date. Format: 2017-01-01_12:00.

properties.name: time_unit
properties.description: (Required) The length of time until a budget resets the actual and forecasted spend. Valid values: MONTHLY, QUARTERLY, ANNUALLY.

properties.name: notification
properties.description: (Optional) Object containing Budget Notifications. Can be used multiple times to define more than one budget notification
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the environment.

properties.name: instance_type
properties.description: (Required) The type of instance to connect to the environment, e.g. t2.micro.

properties.name: automatic_stop_time_minutes
properties.description: (Optional) The number of minutes until the running instance is shut down after the environment has last been used.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The description of the environment.

properties.name: owner_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the environment owner. This can be ARN of any AWS IAM principal. Defaults to the environment's creator.

properties.name: subnet_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the subnet in Amazon VPC that AWS Cloud9 will use to communicate with the Amazon EC2 instance.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Stack name.

properties.name: template_body
properties.description: (Optional) Structure containing the template body (max size: 51,200 bytes).

properties.name: template_url
properties.description: (Optional) Location of a file containing the template body (max size: 460,800 bytes).

properties.name: capabilities
properties.description: (Optional) A list of capabilities. Valid values: CAPABILITY_IAM, CAPABILITY_NAMED_IAM, or CAPABILITY_AUTO_EXPAND

properties.name: disable_rollback
properties.description: (Optional) Set to true to disable rollback of the stack if stack creation failed. Conflicts with on_failure.

properties.name: notification_arns
properties.description: (Optional) A list of SNS topic ARNs to publish stack related events.

properties.name: on_failure
properties.description: (Optional) Action to be taken if stack creation fails. This must be one of: DO_NOTHING, ROLLBACK, or DELETE. Conflicts with disable_rollback.

properties.name: parameters
properties.description: (Optional) A map of Parameter structures that specify input parameters for the stack.

properties.name: policy_body
properties.description: (Optional) Structure containing the stack policy body. Conflicts w/ policy_url.

properties.name: policy_url
properties.description: (Optional) Location of a file containing the stack policy. Conflicts w/ policy_body.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A list of tags to associate with this stack.

properties.name: iam_role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of an IAM role that AWS CloudFormation assumes to create the stack. If you don't specify a value, AWS CloudFormation uses the role that was previously associated with the stack. If no role is available, AWS CloudFormation uses a temporary session that is generated from your user credentials.

properties.name: timeout_in_minutes
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time that can pass before the stack status becomes CREATE_FAILED.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: administration_role_arn
properties.description: (Required) Amazon Resource Number (ARN) of the IAM Role in the administrator account.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Name of the Stack Set. The name must be unique in the region where you create your Stack Set. The name can contain only alphanumeric characters (case-sensitive) and hyphens. It must start with an alphabetic character and cannot be longer than 128 characters.

properties.name: capabilities
properties.description: (Optional) A list of capabilities. Valid values: CAPABILITY_IAM, CAPABILITY_NAMED_IAM, CAPABILITY_AUTO_EXPAND.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Description of the Stack Set.

properties.name: execution_role_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the IAM Role in all target accounts for Stack Set operations. Defaults to AWSCloudFormationStackSetExecutionRole.

properties.name: parameters
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value map of input parameters for the Stack Set template. All template parameters, including those with a Default, must be configured or ignored with lifecycle configuration block ignore_changes argument. All NoEcho template parameters must be ignored with the lifecycle configuration block ignore_changes argument.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value map of tags to associate with this Stack Set and the Stacks created from it. AWS CloudFormation also propagates these tags to supported resources that are created in the Stacks. A maximum number of 50 tags can be specified.

properties.name: template_body
properties.description: (Optional) String containing the CloudFormation template body. Maximum size: 51,200 bytes. Conflicts with template_url.

properties.name: template_url
properties.description: (Optional) String containing the location of a file containing the CloudFormation template body. The URL must point to a template that is located in an Amazon S3 bucket. Maximum location file size: 460,800 bytes. Conflicts with template_body.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: stack_set_name
properties.description: (Required) Name of the Stack Set.

properties.name: account_id
properties.description: (Optional) Target AWS Account ID to create a Stack based on the Stack Set. Defaults to current account.

properties.name: parameter_overrides
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value map of input parameters to override from the Stack Set for this Instance.

properties.name: region
properties.description: (Optional) Target AWS Region to create a Stack based on the Stack Set. Defaults to current region.

properties.name: retain_stack
properties.description: (Optional) During Terraform resource destroy, remove Instance from Stack Set while keeping the Stack and its associated resources. Must be enabled in Terraform state before destroy operation to take effect. You cannot reassociate a retained Stack or add an existing, saved Stack to a new Stack Set. Defaults to false.
The CloudFront distribution argument layout is a complex structure composed of several sub-resources - these resources are laid out below.

properties.name: top-level-arguments
properties.description: » Top-Level Arguments

properties.name: aliases
properties.description: • aliases (Optional) - Extra CNAMEs (alternate domain names), if any, for this distribution.

properties.name: comment
properties.description: • comment (Optional) - Any comments you want to include about the distribution.

properties.name: custom_error_response
properties.description: • custom_error_response (Optional) - One or more custom error response elements (multiples allowed).

properties.name: default_cache_behavior
properties.description: • default_cache_behavior (Required) - The default cache behavior for this distribution (maximum one).

properties.name: default_root_object
properties.description: • default_root_object (Optional) - The object that you want CloudFront to return (for example, index.html) when an end user requests the root URL.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: • enabled (Required) - Whether the distribution is enabled to accept end user requests for content.

properties.name: is_ipv6_enabled
properties.description: • is_ipv6_enabled (Optional) - Whether the IPv6 is enabled for the distribution.

properties.name: http_version
properties.description: • http_version (Optional) - The maximum HTTP version to support on the distribution. Allowed values are http1.1 and http2. The default is http2.

properties.name: logging_config
properties.description: • logging_config (Optional) - The logging configuration that controls how logs are written to your distribution (maximum one).

properties.name: ordered_cache_behavior
properties.description: • ordered_cache_behavior (Optional) - An ordered list of cache behaviors resource for this distribution. List from top to bottom in order of precedence. The topmost cache behavior will have precedence 0.

properties.name: origin
properties.description: • origin (Required) - One or more origins for this distribution (multiples allowed).

properties.name: origin_group
properties.description: • origin_group (Required) - One or more origin_group for this distribution (multiples allowed).

properties.name: price_class
properties.description: • price_class (Optional) - The price class for this distribution. One of PriceClass_All, PriceClass_200, PriceClass_100

properties.name: restrictions
properties.description: • restrictions (Required) - The restriction configuration for this distribution (maximum one).

properties.name: tags
properties.description: • tags - (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: viewer_certificate
properties.description: • viewer_certificate (Required) - The SSL configuration for this distribution (maximum one).

properties.name: web_acl_id
properties.description: • web_acl_id (Optional) - If you're using AWS WAF to filter CloudFront requests, the Id of the AWS WAF web ACL that is associated with the distribution. The WAF Web ACL must exist in the WAF Global (CloudFront) region and the credentials configuring this argument must have waf:GetWebACL permissions assigned.

properties.name: retain_on_delete
properties.description: • retain_on_delete (Optional) - Disables the distribution instead of deleting it when destroying the resource through Terraform. If this is set, the distribution needs to be deleted manually afterwards. Default: false.

properties.name: wait_for_deployment
properties.description: • wait_for_deployment (Optional) - If enabled, the resource will wait for the distribution status to change from InProgress to Deployed. Setting this tofalse will skip the process. Default: true.

properties.name: cache-behavior-arguments
properties.description: » Cache Behavior Arguments

properties.name: allowed_methods
properties.description: • allowed_methods (Required) - Controls which HTTP methods CloudFront processes and forwards to your Amazon S3 bucket or your custom origin.

properties.name: cached_methods
properties.description: • cached_methods (Required) - Controls whether CloudFront caches the response to requests using the specified HTTP methods.

properties.name: compress
properties.description: • compress (Optional) - Whether you want CloudFront to automatically compress content for web requests that include Accept-Encoding: gzip in the request header (default: false).

properties.name: default_ttl
properties.description: • default_ttl (Optional) - The default amount of time (in seconds) that an object is in a CloudFront cache before CloudFront forwards another request in the absence of an Cache-Control max-age or Expires header. Defaults to 1 day.

properties.name: field_level_encryption_id
properties.description: • field_level_encryption_id (Optional) - Field level encryption configuration ID

properties.name: forwarded_values
properties.description: • forwarded_values (Required) - The forwarded values configuration that specifies how CloudFront handles query strings, cookies and headers (maximum one).

properties.name: lambda_function_association
properties.description: • lambda_function_association (Optional) - A config block that triggers a lambda function with specific actions. Defined below, maximum 4.

properties.name: max_ttl
properties.description: • max_ttl (Optional) - The maximum amount of time (in seconds) that an object is in a CloudFront cache before CloudFront forwards another request to your origin to determine whether the object has been updated. Only effective in the presence of Cache-Control max-age, Cache-Control s-maxage, and Expires headers. Defaults to 365 days.

properties.name: min_ttl
properties.description: • min_ttl (Optional) - The minimum amount of time that you want objects to stay in CloudFront caches before CloudFront queries your origin to see whether the object has been updated. Defaults to 0 seconds.

properties.name: path_pattern
properties.description: • path_pattern (Required) - The pattern (for example, images/*.jpg) that specifies which requests you want this cache behavior to apply to.

properties.name: smooth_streaming
properties.description: • smooth_streaming (Optional) - Indicates whether you want to distribute media files in Microsoft Smooth Streaming format using the origin that is associated with this cache behavior.

properties.name: target_origin_id
properties.description: • target_origin_id (Required) - The value of ID for the origin that you want CloudFront to route requests to when a request matches the path pattern either for a cache behavior or for the default cache behavior.

properties.name: trusted_signers
properties.description: • trusted_signers (Optional) - The AWS accounts, if any, that you want to allow to create signed URLs for private content.

properties.name: viewer_protocol_policy
properties.description: • viewer_protocol_policy (Required) - Use this element to specify the protocol that users can use to access the files in the origin specified by TargetOriginId when a request matches the path pattern in PathPattern. One of allow-all, https-only, or redirect-to-https.

properties.name: forwarded-values-arguments
properties.description: » Forwarded Values Arguments

properties.name: cookies
properties.description: • cookies (Required) - The forwarded values cookies that specifies how CloudFront handles cookies (maximum one).

properties.name: headers
properties.description: • headers (Optional) - Specifies the Headers, if any, that you want CloudFront to vary upon for this cache behavior. Specify * to include all headers.

properties.name: query_string
properties.description: • query_string (Required) - Indicates whether you want CloudFront to forward query strings to the origin that is associated with this cache behavior.

properties.name: query_string_cache_keys
properties.description: • query_string_cache_keys (Optional) - When specified, along with a value of true for query_string, all query strings are forwarded, however only the query string keys listed in this argument are cached. When omitted with a value of true for query_string, all query string keys are cached.

properties.name: lambda-function-association
properties.description: » Lambda Function Association
Lambda@Edge allows you to associate an AWS Lambda Function with a predefined event. You can associate a single function per event type. See What is Lambda@Edge for more information.
Example configuration:

resource "aws_cloudfront_distribution" "example" {
  # ... other configuration ...

  # lambda_function_association is also supported by default_cache_behavior
  ordered_cache_behavior {
    # ... other configuration ...

    lambda_function_association {
      event_type   = "viewer-request"
      lambda_arn   = "${aws_lambda_function.example.qualified_arn}"
      include_body = false
    }
  }
}

properties.name: event_type
properties.description: (Required) - The specific event to trigger this function. Valid values: viewer-request, origin-request, viewer-response, origin-response

properties.name: lambda_arn
properties.description: (Required) - ARN of the Lambda function.

properties.name: include_body
properties.description: (Optional) - When set to true it exposes the request body to the lambda function. Defaults to false. Valid values: true, false.

properties.name: cookies-arguments
properties.description: » Cookies Arguments

properties.name: forward
properties.description: • forward (Required) - Specifies whether you want CloudFront to forward cookies to the origin that is associated with this cache behavior. You can specify all, none or whitelist. If whitelist, you must include the subsequent whitelisted_names

properties.name: whitelisted_names
properties.description: • whitelisted_names (Optional) - If you have specified whitelist to forward, the whitelisted cookies that you want CloudFront to forward to your origin.

properties.name: custom-error-response-arguments
properties.description: » Custom Error Response Arguments

properties.name: error_caching_min_ttl
properties.description: • error_caching_min_ttl (Optional) - The minimum amount of time you want HTTP error codes to stay in CloudFront caches before CloudFront queries your origin to see whether the object has been updated.

properties.name: error_code
properties.description: • error_code (Required) - The 4xx or 5xx HTTP status code that you want to customize.

properties.name: response_code
properties.description: • response_code (Optional) - The HTTP status code that you want CloudFront to return with the custom error page to the viewer.

properties.name: response_page_path
properties.description: • response_page_path (Optional) - The path of the custom error page (for example, /custom_404.html).

properties.name: default-cache-behavior-arguments
properties.description: » Default Cache Behavior Arguments
The arguments for default_cache_behavior are the same as for ordered_cache_behavior, except for the path_pattern argument is not required.

properties.name: logging-config-arguments
properties.description: » Logging Config Arguments

properties.name: bucket
properties.description: • bucket (Required) - The Amazon S3 bucket to store the access logs in, for example, myawslogbucket.s3.amazonaws.com.

properties.name: include_cookies
properties.description: • include_cookies (Optional) - Specifies whether you want CloudFront to include cookies in access logs (default: false).

properties.name: prefix
properties.description: • prefix (Optional) - An optional string that you want CloudFront to prefix to the access log filenames for this distribution, for example, myprefix/.

properties.name: origin-arguments
properties.description: » Origin Arguments

properties.name: custom_origin_config
properties.description: • custom_origin_config - The CloudFront custom origin configuration information. If an S3 origin is required, use s3_origin_config instead.

properties.name: domain_name
properties.description: • domain_name (Required) - The DNS domain name of either the S3 bucket, or web site of your custom origin.

properties.name: custom_header
properties.description: • custom_header (Optional) - One or more sub-resources with name and value parameters that specify header data that will be sent to the origin (multiples allowed).

properties.name: origin_id
properties.description: • origin_id (Required) - A unique identifier for the origin.

properties.name: origin_path
properties.description: • origin_path (Optional) - An optional element that causes CloudFront to request your content from a directory in your Amazon S3 bucket or your custom origin.

properties.name: s3_origin_config
properties.description: • s3_origin_config - The CloudFront S3 origin configuration information. If a custom origin is required, use custom_origin_config instead.

properties.name: custom-origin-config-arguments
properties.description: » Custom Origin Config Arguments

properties.name: http_port
properties.description: • http_port (Required) - The HTTP port the custom origin listens on.

properties.name: https_port
properties.description: • https_port (Required) - The HTTPS port the custom origin listens on.

properties.name: origin_protocol_policy
properties.description: • origin_protocol_policy (Required) - The origin protocol policy to apply to your origin. One of http-only, https-only, or match-viewer.

properties.name: origin_ssl_protocols
properties.description: • origin_ssl_protocols (Required) - The SSL/TLS protocols that you want CloudFront to use when communicating with your origin over HTTPS. A list of one or more of SSLv3, TLSv1, TLSv1.1, and TLSv1.2.

properties.name: origin_keepalive_timeout
properties.description: • origin_keepalive_timeout - (Optional) The Custom KeepAlive timeout, in seconds. By default, AWS enforces a limit of 60. But you can request an increase.

properties.name: origin_read_timeout
properties.description: • origin_read_timeout - (Optional) The Custom Read timeout, in seconds. By default, AWS enforces a limit of 60. But you can request an increase.

properties.name: s3-origin-config-arguments
properties.description: » S3 Origin Config Arguments

properties.name: origin_access_identity
properties.description: (Optional) - The CloudFront origin access identity to associate with the origin.

properties.name: origin-group-arguments
properties.description: » Origin Group Arguments

properties.name: origin_id
properties.description: • origin_id (Required) - A unique identifier for the origin group.

properties.name: failover_criteria
properties.description: • failover_criteria (Required) - The failover criteria for when to failover to the secondary origin

properties.name: member
properties.description: • member (Required) - Ordered member configuration blocks assigned to the origin group, where the first member is the primary origin. Minimum 2.

properties.name: failover-criteria-arguments
properties.description: » Failover Criteria Arguments

properties.name: status_codes
properties.description: (Required) - A list of HTTP status codes for the origin group

properties.name: member-arguments
properties.description: » Member Arguments

properties.name: origin_id
properties.description: (Required) - The unique identifier of the member origin

properties.name: restrictions-arguments
properties.description: » Restrictions Arguments
The restrictions sub-resource takes another single sub-resource named geo_restriction (see the example for usage).
The arguments of geo_restriction are:

properties.name: locations
properties.description: • locations (Optional) - The ISO 3166-1-alpha-2 codes for which you want CloudFront either to distribute your content (whitelist) or not distribute your content (blacklist).

properties.name: restriction_type
properties.description: • restriction_type (Required) - The method that you want to use to restrict distribution of your content by country: none, whitelist, or blacklist.

properties.name: viewer-certificate-arguments
properties.description: » Viewer Certificate Arguments

properties.name: acm_certificate_arn
properties.description: • acm_certificate_arn - The ARN of the AWS Certificate Manager certificate that you wish to use with this distribution. Specify this, cloudfront_default_certificate, or iam_certificate_id. The ACM certificate must be in US-EAST-1.

properties.name: cloudfront_default_certificate
properties.description: • cloudfront_default_certificate - true if you want viewers to use HTTPS to request your objects and you're using the CloudFront domain name for your distribution. Specify this, acm_certificate_arn, or iam_certificate_id.

properties.name: iam_certificate_id
properties.description: • iam_certificate_id - The IAM certificate identifier of the custom viewer certificate for this distribution if you are using a custom domain. Specify this, acm_certificate_arn, or cloudfront_default_certificate.

properties.name: minimum_protocol_version
properties.description: • minimum_protocol_version - The minimum version of the SSL protocol that you want CloudFront to use for HTTPS connections. One of SSLv3, TLSv1, TLSv1_2016, TLSv1.1_2016 or TLSv1.2_2018. Default: TLSv1. NOTE: If you are using a custom certificate (specified with acm_certificate_arn or iam_certificate_id), and have specified sni-only in ssl_support_method, TLSv1 or later must be specified. If you have specified vip in ssl_support_method, only SSLv3 or TLSv1 can be specified. If you have specified cloudfront_default_certificate, TLSv1 must be specified.

properties.name: ssl_support_method
properties.description: • ssl_support_method: Specifies how you want CloudFront to serve HTTPS requests. One of vip or sni-only. Required if you specify acm_certificate_arn or iam_certificate_id. NOTE: vip causes CloudFront to use a dedicated IP address and may incur extra charges.

properties.name: comment
properties.description: (Optional) - An optional comment for the origin access identity.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: comment
properties.description: (Optional) An optional comment about the public key.

properties.name: encoded_key
properties.description: (Required) The encoded public key that you want to add to CloudFront to use with features like field-level encryption.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name for the public key. By default generated by Terraform.

properties.name: name_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) The name for the public key. Conflicts with name.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: source_backup_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) The id of Cloud HSM v2 cluster backup to be restored.

properties.name: hsm_type
properties.description: (Required) The type of HSM module in the cluster. Currently, only hsm1.medium is supported.

properties.name: subnet_ids
properties.description: (Required) The IDs of subnets in which cluster will operate.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: cluster_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of Cloud HSM v2 cluster to which HSM will be added.

properties.name: subnet_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of subnet in which HSM module will be located.

properties.name: availability_zone
properties.description: (Optional) The IDs of AZ in which HSM module will be located. Do not use together with subnet_id.

properties.name: ip_address
properties.description: (Optional) The IP address of HSM module. Must be within the CIDR of selected subnet.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the trail.

properties.name: s3_bucket_name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the S3 bucket designated for publishing log files.

properties.name: s3_key_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the S3 key prefix that follows the name of the bucket you have designated for log file delivery.

properties.name: cloud_watch_logs_role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the role for the CloudWatch Logs endpoint to assume to write to a user’s log group.

properties.name: cloud_watch_logs_group_arn
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies a log group name using an Amazon Resource Name (ARN), that represents the log group to which CloudTrail logs will be delivered.

properties.name: enable_logging
properties.description: (Optional) Enables logging for the trail. Defaults to true. Setting this to false will pause logging.

properties.name: include_global_service_events
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the trail is publishing events from global services such as IAM to the log files. Defaults to true.

properties.name: is_multi_region_trail
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the trail is created in the current region or in all regions. Defaults to false.

properties.name: is_organization_trail
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the trail is an AWS Organizations trail. Organization trails log events for the master account and all member accounts. Can only be created in the organization master account. Defaults to false.

properties.name: sns_topic_name
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the name of the Amazon SNS topic defined for notification of log file delivery.

properties.name: enable_log_file_validation
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether log file integrity validation is enabled. Defaults to false.

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the KMS key ARN to use to encrypt the logs delivered by CloudTrail.

properties.name: event_selector
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies an event selector for enabling data event logging. Fields documented below. Please note the CloudTrail limits when configuring these.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the trail

properties.name: event-selector-arguments
properties.description: » Event Selector Arguments
For event_selector the following attributes are supported.

properties.name: read_write_type
properties.description: (Optional) - Specify if you want your trail to log read-only events, write-only events, or all. By default, the value is All. You can specify only the following value: "ReadOnly", "WriteOnly", "All". Defaults to All.

properties.name: include_management_events
properties.description: (Optional) - Specify if you want your event selector to include management events for your trail.

properties.name: data_resource
properties.description: (Optional) - Specifies logging data events. Fields documented below.

properties.name: data-resource-arguments
properties.description: » Data Resource Arguments
For data_resource the following attributes are supported.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) - The resource type in which you want to log data events. You can specify only the follwing value: "AWS::S3::Object", "AWS::Lambda::Function"

properties.name: values
properties.description: (Required) - A list of ARN for the specified S3 buckets and object prefixes..
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: dashboard_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the dashboard.

properties.name: dashboard_body
properties.description: (Required) The detailed information about the dashboard, including what widgets are included and their location on the dashboard. You can read more about the body structure in the documentation.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: principal
properties.description: (Required) The 12-digit AWS account ID that you are permitting to put events to your default event bus. Specify * to permit any account to put events to your default event bus, optionally limited by condition.

properties.name: statement_id
properties.description: (Required) An identifier string for the external account that you are granting permissions to.

properties.name: action
properties.description: (Optional) The action that you are enabling the other account to perform. Defaults to events:PutEvents.

properties.name: condition
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration block to limit the event bus permissions you are granting to only accounts that fulfill the condition. Specified below.

properties.name: condition-1
properties.description: » condition

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Required) Key for the condition. Valid values: aws:PrincipalOrgID.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) Type of condition. Value values: StringEquals.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) Value for the key.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The rule's name. By default generated by Terraform.

properties.name: name_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) The rule's name. Conflicts with name.

properties.name: schedule_expression
properties.description: (Required, if event_pattern isn't specified) The scheduling expression. For example, cron(0 20 * * ? *) or rate(5 minutes).

properties.name: event_pattern
properties.description: (Required, if schedule_expression isn't specified) Event pattern described a JSON object. See full documentation of CloudWatch Events and Event Patterns for details.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The description of the rule.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) associated with the role that is used for target invocation.

properties.name: is_enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the rule should be enabled (defaults to true).

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
Note: input and input_path are mutually exclusive options.

Note: In order to be able to have your AWS Lambda function or SNS topic invoked by a CloudWatch Events rule, you must setup the right permissions using aws_lambda_permission or aws_sns_topic.policy. More info here.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: rule
properties.description: (Required) The name of the rule you want to add targets to.

properties.name: target_id
properties.description: (Optional) The unique target assignment ID. If missing, will generate a random, unique id.

properties.name: arn
properties.description: (Required) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) associated of the target.

properties.name: input
properties.description: (Optional) Valid JSON text passed to the target.

properties.name: input_path
properties.description: (Optional) The value of the JSONPath that is used for extracting part of the matched event when passing it to the target.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role to be used for this target when the rule is triggered. Required if ecs_target is used.

properties.name: run_command_targets
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are using the rule to invoke Amazon EC2 Run Command. Documented below. A maximum of 5 are allowed.

properties.name: ecs_target
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are using the rule to invoke Amazon ECS Task. Documented below. A maximum of 1 are allowed.

properties.name: batch_target
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are using the rule to invoke an Amazon Batch Job. Documented below. A maximum of 1 are allowed.

properties.name: kinesis_target
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are using the rule to invoke an Amazon Kinesis Stream. Documented below. A maximum of 1 are allowed.

properties.name: sqs_target
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are using the rule to invoke an Amazon SQS Queue. Documented below. A maximum of 1 are allowed.

properties.name: input_transformer
properties.description: (Optional) Parameters used when you are providing a custom input to a target based on certain event data.
run_command_targets support the following:

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Required) Can be either tag:tag-key or InstanceIds.

properties.name: values
properties.description: (Required) If Key is tag:tag-key, Values is a list of tag values. If Key is InstanceIds, Values is a list of Amazon EC2 instance IDs.
ecs_target support the following:

properties.name: group
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies an ECS task group for the task. The maximum length is 255 characters.

properties.name: launch_type
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the launch type on which your task is running. The launch type that you specify here must match one of the launch type (compatibilities) of the target task. Valid values are EC2 or FARGATE.

properties.name: network_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Use this if the ECS task uses the awsvpc network mode. This specifies the VPC subnets and security groups associated with the task, and whether a public IP address is to be used. Required if launch_type is FARGATE because the awsvpc mode is required for Fargate tasks.

properties.name: platform_version
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the platform version for the task. Specify only the numeric portion of the platform version, such as 1.1.0. This is used only if LaunchType is FARGATE. For more information about valid platform versions, see AWS Fargate Platform Versions.

properties.name: task_count
properties.description: (Optional) The number of tasks to create based on the TaskDefinition. The default is 1.

properties.name: task_definition_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the task definition to use if the event target is an Amazon ECS cluster.
network_configuration support the following:

properties.name: subnets
properties.description: (Required) The subnets associated with the task or service.

properties.name: security_groups
properties.description: (Optional) The security groups associated with the task or service. If you do not specify a security group, the default security group for the VPC is used.

properties.name: assign_public_ip
properties.description: (Optional) Assign a public IP address to the ENI (Fargate launch type only). Valid values are true or false. Default false.
For more information, see Task Networking
