properties.name: ec2_tag_filter
properties.description: (Optional) Tag filters associated with the deployment group. See the AWS docs for details.

properties.name: ec2_tag_set
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration block(s) of Tag filters associated with the deployment group, which are also referred to as tag groups (documented below). See the AWS docs for details.

properties.name: ecs_service
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration block(s) of the ECS services for a deployment group (documented below).

properties.name: load_balancer_info
properties.description: (Optional) Single configuration block of the load balancer to use in a blue/green deployment (documented below).

properties.name: on_premises_instance_tag_filter
properties.description: (Optional) On premise tag filters associated with the group. See the AWS docs for details.

properties.name: trigger_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration block(s) of the triggers for the deployment group (documented below).

properties.name: alarm_configuration-argument-reference
properties.description: » alarm_configuration Argument Reference
You can configure a deployment to stop when a CloudWatch alarm detects that a metric has fallen below or exceeded a defined threshold. alarm_configuration supports the following:

properties.name: alarms
properties.description: (Optional) A list of alarms configured for the deployment group. A maximum of 10 alarms can be added to a deployment group.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether the alarm configuration is enabled. This option is useful when you want to temporarily deactivate alarm monitoring for a deployment group without having to add the same alarms again later.

properties.name: list description
true
properties.description: : The deployment will proceed even if alarm status information can't be retrieved.

properties.name: false
properties.description: : The deployment will stop if alarm status information can't be retrieved.
Only one alarm_configuration is allowed.

properties.name: auto_rollback_configuration-argument-reference
properties.description: » auto_rollback_configuration Argument Reference

You can configure a deployment group to automatically rollback when a deployment fails or when a monitoring threshold you specify is met. In this case, the last known good version of an application revision is deployed. auto_rollback_configuration supports the following:

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether a defined automatic rollback configuration is currently enabled for this Deployment Group. If you enable automatic rollback, you must specify at least one event type.

properties.name: events
properties.description: (Optional) The event type or types that trigger a rollback. Supported types are DEPLOYMENT_FAILURE and DEPLOYMENT_STOP_ON_ALARM.
Only one `auto_rollback configuration` is allowed_.

properties.name: blue_green_deployment_config-argument-reference
properties.description: » blue_green_deployment_config Argument Reference
You can configure options for a blue/green deployment. blue_green_deployment_config supports the following:

properties.name: deployment_ready_option
properties.description: (Optional) Information about the action to take when newly provisioned instances are ready to receive traffic in a blue/green deployment (documented below).

properties.name: green_fleet_provisioning_option
properties.description: (Optional) Information about how instances are provisioned for a replacement environment in a blue/green deployment (documented below).

properties.name: terminate_blue_instances_on_deployment_success
properties.description: (Optional) Information about whether to terminate instances in the original fleet during a blue/green deployment (documented below).
Only one blue_green_deployment_config is allowed.
You can configure how traffic is rerouted to instances in a replacement environment in a blue/green deployment. deployment_ready_option supports the following:

properties.name: list description
CONTINUE_DEPLOYMENT
properties.description: : Register new instances with the load balancer immediately after the new application revision is installed on the instances in the replacement environment.

properties.name: STOP_DEPLOYMENT
properties.description: : Do not register new instances with load balancer unless traffic is rerouted manually. If traffic is not rerouted manually before the end of the specified wait period, the deployment status is changed to Stopped.

properties.name: wait_time_in_minutes
properties.description: (Optional) The number of minutes to wait before the status of a blue/green deployment changed to Stopped if rerouting is not started manually. Applies only to the STOP_DEPLOYMENT option for action_on_timeout.
You can configure how instances will be added to the replacement environment in a blue/green deployment. green_fleet_provisioning_option supports the following:

properties.name: list description
DISCOVER_EXISTING
properties.description: : Use instances that already exist or will be created manually.

properties.name: COPY_AUTO_SCALING_GROUP
properties.description: : Use settings from a specified Auto Scaling group to define and create instances in a new Auto Scaling group. Exactly one Auto Scaling group must be specified when selecting COPY_AUTO_SCALING_GROUP. Use autoscaling_groups to specify the Auto Scaling group.
You can configure how instances in the original environment are terminated when a blue/green deployment is successful. terminate_blue_instances_on_deployment_success supports the following:

properties.name: list description
TERMINATE
properties.description: : Instances are terminated after a specified wait time.

properties.name: KEEP_ALIVE
properties.description: : Instances are left running after they are deregistered from the load balancer and removed from the deployment group.

properties.name: termination_wait_time_in_minutes
properties.description: (Optional) The number of minutes to wait after a successful blue/green deployment before terminating instances from the original environment.

properties.name: deployment_style-argument-reference
properties.description: » deployment_style Argument Reference
You can configure the type of deployment, either in-place or blue/green, you want to run and whether to route deployment traffic behind a load balancer. deployment_style supports the following:

properties.name: deployment_option
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether to route deployment traffic behind a load balancer. Valid Values are WITH_TRAFFIC_CONTROL or WITHOUT_TRAFFIC_CONTROL.

properties.name: deployment_type
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether to run an in-place deployment or a blue/green deployment. Valid Values are IN_PLACE or BLUE_GREEN.
Only one deployment_style is allowed.

properties.name: ec2_tag_filter-argument-reference
properties.description: » ec2_tag_filter Argument Reference
The ec2_tag_filter configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Optional) The key of the tag filter.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of the tag filter, either KEY_ONLY, VALUE_ONLY, or KEY_AND_VALUE.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Optional) The value of the tag filter.
Multiple occurrences of ec2_tag_filter are allowed, where any instance that matches to at least one of the tag filters is selected.

properties.name: ec2_tag_set-argument-reference
properties.description: » ec2_tag_set Argument Reference
You can form a tag group by putting a set of tag filters into ec2_tag_set. If multiple tag groups are specified, any instance that matches to at least one tag filter of every tag group is selected.

properties.name: ecs_service-argument-reference
properties.description: » ecs_service Argument Reference
Each ecs_service configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: cluster_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the ECS cluster.

properties.name: service_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the ECS service.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info Argument Reference
You can configure the Load Balancer to use in a deployment. load_balancer_info supports the following:

properties.name: elb_info
properties.description: (Optional) The Classic Elastic Load Balancer to use in a deployment. Conflicts with target_group_info and target_group_pair_info.

properties.name: target_group_info
properties.description: (Optional) The (Application/Network Load Balancer) target group to use in a deployment. Conflicts with elb_info and target_group_pair_info.

properties.name: target_group_pair_info
properties.description: (Optional) The (Application/Network Load Balancer) target group pair to use in a deployment. Conflicts with elb_info and target_group_info.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-elb_info-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info elb_info Argument Reference
The elb_info configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the load balancer that will be used to route traffic from original instances to replacement instances in a blue/green deployment. For in-place deployments, the name of the load balancer that instances are deregistered from so they are not serving traffic during a deployment, and then re-registered with after the deployment completes.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-target_group_info-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info target_group_info Argument Reference
The target_group_info configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the target group that instances in the original environment are deregistered from, and instances in the replacement environment registered with. For in-place deployments, the name of the target group that instances are deregistered from, so they are not serving traffic during a deployment, and then re-registered with after the deployment completes.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-target_group_pair_info-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info target_group_pair_info Argument Reference
The target_group_pair_info configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: prod_traffic_route
properties.description: (Required) Configuration block for the production traffic route (documented below).

properties.name: target_group
properties.description: (Required) Configuration blocks for a target group within a target group pair (documented below).

properties.name: test_traffic_route
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration block for the test traffic route (documented below).

properties.name: load_balancer_info-target_group_pair_info-prod_traffic_route-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info target_group_pair_info prod_traffic_route Argument Reference
The prod_traffic_route configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: listener_arns
properties.description: (Required) List of Amazon Resource Names (ARNs) of the load balancer listeners.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-target_group_pair_info-target_group-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info target_group_pair_info target_group Argument Reference
The target_group configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Name of the target group.

properties.name: load_balancer_info-target_group_pair_info-test_traffic_route-argument-reference
properties.description: » load_balancer_info target_group_pair_info test_traffic_route Argument Reference
The test_traffic_route configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: listener_arns
properties.description: (Required) List of Amazon Resource Names (ARNs) of the load balancer listeners.

properties.name: on_premises_tag_filter-argument-reference
properties.description: » on_premises_tag_filter Argument Reference
The on_premises_tag_filter configuration block supports the following:

properties.name: key
properties.description: (Optional) The key of the tag filter.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of the tag filter, either KEY_ONLY, VALUE_ONLY, or KEY_AND_VALUE.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Optional) The value of the tag filter.

properties.name: trigger_configuration-argument-reference
properties.description: » trigger_configuration Argument Reference

Add triggers to a Deployment Group to receive notifications about events related to deployments or instances in the group. Notifications are sent to subscribers of the SNS topic associated with the trigger. CodeDeploy must have permission to publish to the topic from this deployment group. trigger_configuration supports the following:

properties.name: trigger_events
properties.description: (Required) The event type or types for which notifications are triggered. Some values that are supported: DeploymentStart, DeploymentSuccess, DeploymentFailure, DeploymentStop, DeploymentRollback, InstanceStart, InstanceSuccess, InstanceFailure. See the CodeDeploy documentation for all possible values.

properties.name: trigger_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the notification trigger.

properties.name: trigger_target_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the SNS topic through which notifications are sent.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the pipeline.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) A service role Amazon Resource Name (ARN) that grants AWS CodePipeline permission to make calls to AWS services on your behalf.

properties.name: artifact_store
properties.description: (Required) An artifact_store block. Artifact stores are documented below.

properties.name: stage
properties.description: (Minimum of at least two stage blocks is required) A stage block. Stages are documented below.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
An artifact_store block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: location
properties.description: (Required) The location where AWS CodePipeline stores artifacts for a pipeline, such as an S3 bucket.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of the artifact store, such as Amazon S3

properties.name: encryption_key
properties.description: (Optional) The encryption key block AWS CodePipeline uses to encrypt the data in the artifact store, such as an AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) key. If you don't specify a key, AWS CodePipeline uses the default key for Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3). An encryption_key block is documented below.
An encryption_key block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: id
properties.description: (Required) The KMS key ARN or ID

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of key; currently only KMS is supported
A stage block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the stage.

properties.name: action
properties.description: (Required) The action(s) to include in the stage. Defined as an action block below
A action block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: category
properties.description: (Required) A category defines what kind of action can be taken in the stage, and constrains the provider type for the action. Possible values are Approval, Build, Deploy, Invoke, Source and Test.

properties.name: owner
properties.description: (Required) The creator of the action being called. Possible values are AWS, Custom and ThirdParty.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The action declaration's name.

properties.name: provider
properties.description: (Required) The provider of the service being called by the action. Valid providers are determined by the action category. For example, an action in the Deploy category type might have a provider of AWS CodeDeploy, which would be specified as CodeDeploy.

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Required) A string that identifies the action type.

properties.name: configuration
properties.description: (Optional) A Map of the action declaration's configuration. Find out more about configuring action configurations in the Reference Pipeline Structure documentation.

properties.name: input_artifacts
properties.description: (Optional) A list of artifact names to be worked on.

properties.name: output_artifacts
properties.description: (Optional) A list of artifact names to output. Output artifact names must be unique within a pipeline.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the IAM service role that will perform the declared action. This is assumed through the roleArn for the pipeline.

properties.name: run_order
properties.description: (Optional) The order in which actions are run.

Note: The input artifact of an action must exactly match the output artifact declared in a preceding action, but the input artifact does not have to be the next action in strict sequence from the action that provided the output artifact. Actions in parallel can declare different output artifacts, which are in turn consumed by different following actions.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the webhook.

properties.name: authentication
properties.description: (Required) The type of authentication to use. One of IP, GITHUB_HMAC, or UNAUTHENTICATED.

properties.name: authentication_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) An auth block. Required for IP and GITHUB_HMAC. Auth blocks are documented below.

properties.name: filter
properties.description: (Required) One or more filter blocks. Filter blocks are documented below.

properties.name: target_action
properties.description: (Required) The name of the action in a pipeline you want to connect to the webhook. The action must be from the source (first) stage of the pipeline.

properties.name: target_pipeline
properties.description: (Required) The name of the pipeline.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
An authentication_configuration block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: secret_token
properties.description: (Optional) The shared secret for the GitHub repository webhook. Set this as secret in your github_repository_webhook's configuration block. Required for GITHUB_HMAC.

properties.name: allowed_ip_range
properties.description: (Optional) A valid CIDR block for IP filtering. Required for IP.
A filter block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: json_path
properties.description: (Required) The JSON path to filter on.

properties.name: match_equals
properties.description: (Required) The value to match on (e.g. refs/heads/{Branch}). See AWS docs for details.
The Cognito Identity Pool argument layout is a structure composed of several sub-resources - these resources are laid out below.

properties.name: identity_pool_name
properties.description: (Required) - The Cognito Identity Pool name.

properties.name: allow_unauthenticated_identities
properties.description: (Required) - Whether the identity pool supports unauthenticated logins or not.

properties.name: developer_provider_name
properties.description: (Optional) - The "domain" by which Cognito will refer to your users. This name acts as a placeholder that allows your backend and the Cognito service to communicate about the developer provider.

properties.name: cognito_identity_providers
properties.description: (Optional) - An array of Amazon Cognito Identity user pools and their client IDs.

properties.name: openid_connect_provider_arns
properties.description: (Optional) - A list of OpendID Connect provider ARNs.

properties.name: saml_provider_arns
properties.description: (Optional) - An array of Amazon Resource Names (ARNs) of the SAML provider for your identity.

properties.name: supported_login_providers
properties.description: (Optional) - Key-Value pairs mapping provider names to provider app IDs.

properties.name: cognito-identity-providers
properties.description: » Cognito Identity Providers

properties.name: client_id
properties.description: (Optional) - The client ID for the Amazon Cognito Identity User Pool.

properties.name: provider_name
properties.description: (Optional) - The provider name for an Amazon Cognito Identity User Pool.

properties.name: server_side_token_check
properties.description: (Optional) - Whether server-side token validation is enabled for the identity provider’s token or not.
The Cognito Identity Pool Roles Attachment argument layout is a structure composed of several sub-resources - these resources are laid out below.

properties.name: identity_pool_id
properties.description: (Required) - An identity pool ID in the format REGION:GUID.

properties.name: role_mapping
properties.description: (Optional) - A List of Role Mapping.

properties.name: roles
properties.description: (Required) - The map of roles associated with this pool. For a given role, the key will be either "authenticated" or "unauthenticated" and the value will be the Role ARN.

properties.name: role-mappings
properties.description: » Role Mappings

properties.name: identity_provider
properties.description: (Required) - A string identifying the identity provider, for example, "graph.facebook.com" or "cognito-idp.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/us-east-1_abcdefghi:app_client_id".

properties.name: ambiguous_role_resolution
properties.description: (Optional) - Specifies the action to be taken if either no rules match the claim value for the Rules type, or there is no cognito:preferred_role claim and there are multiple cognito:roles matches for the Token type. Required if you specify Token or Rules as the Type.

properties.name: mapping_rule
properties.description: (Optional) - The Rules Configuration to be used for mapping users to roles. You can specify up to 25 rules per identity provider. Rules are evaluated in order. The first one to match specifies the role.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) - The role mapping type.

properties.name: rules-configuration
properties.description: » Rules Configuration

properties.name: claim
properties.description: (Required) - The claim name that must be present in the token, for example, "isAdmin" or "paid".

properties.name: match_type
properties.description: (Required) - The match condition that specifies how closely the claim value in the IdP token must match Value.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) - The role ARN.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) - A brief string that the claim must match, for example, "paid" or "yes".
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: user_pool_id
properties.description: (Required) - The user pool id

properties.name: provider_name
properties.description: (Required) - The provider name

properties.name: provider_type
properties.description: (Required) - The provider type. See AWS API for valid values

properties.name: attribute_mapping

properties.name: idp_identifiers
properties.description: (Optional) - The list of identity providers.

properties.name: provider_details
properties.description: (Optional) - The map of identity details, such as access token
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: identifier

properties.name: name

properties.name: scope

properties.name: authorization-scope

properties.name: scope_name

NOTE: When defining an attribute_data_type of String or Number, the respective attribute constraints configuration block (e.g string_attribute_constraints or number_attribute_contraints) is required to prevent recreation of the Terraform resource. properties.name: string_attribute_constraints

properties.name: number-attribute-constraints

properties.name: max_value
properties.description: (Optional) - The maximum value of an attribute that is of the number data type.

properties.name: min_value

properties.name: options-argument-reference
properties.description: » options Argument Reference
NOTE: If atime is set to BEST_EFFORT, mtime must be set to PRESERVE. If atime is set to NONE, mtime must be set to NONE.
The following arguments are supported inside the options configuration block:

properties.name: atime
properties.description: (Optional) A file metadata that shows the last time a file was accessed (that is when the file was read or written to). If set to BEST_EFFORT, the DataSync Task attempts to preserve the original (that is, the version before sync PREPARING phase) atime attribute on all source files. Valid values: BEST_EFFORT, NONE. Default: BEST_EFFORT.

properties.name: bytes_per_second
properties.description: (Optional) Limits the bandwidth utilized. For example, to set a maximum of 1 MB, set this value to 1048576. Value values: -1 or greater. Default: -1 (unlimited).

properties.name: gid
properties.description: (Optional) Group identifier of the file's owners. Valid values: BOTH, INT_VALUE, NAME, NONE. Default: INT_VALUE (preserve integer value of the ID).

properties.name: mtime
properties.description: (Optional) A file metadata that indicates the last time a file was modified (written to) before the sync PREPARING phase. Value values: NONE, PRESERVE. Default: PRESERVE.

properties.name: posix_permissions
properties.description: (Optional) Determines which users or groups can access a file for a specific purpose such as reading, writing, or execution of the file. Valid values: BEST_EFFORT, NONE, PRESERVE. Default: PRESERVE.

properties.name: preserve_deleted_files
properties.description: (Optional) Whether files deleted in the source should be removed or preserved in the destination file system. Valid values: PRESERVE, REMOVE. Default: PRESERVE.

properties.name: preserve_devices
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the DataSync Task should preserve the metadata of block and character devices in the source files system, and recreate the files with that device name and metadata on the destination. The DataSync Task can’t sync the actual contents of such devices, because many of the devices are non-terminal and don’t return an end of file (EOF) marker. Valid values: NONE, PRESERVE. Default: NONE (ignore special devices).

properties.name: uid
properties.description: (Optional) User identifier of the file's owners. Valid values: BOTH, INT_VALUE, NAME, NONE. Default: INT_VALUE (preserve integer value of the ID).

properties.name: verify_mode
properties.description: (Optional) Whether a data integrity verification should be performed at the end of a task execution after all data and metadata have been transferred. Valid values: NONE, POINT_IN_TIME_CONSISTENT. Default: POINT_IN_TIME_CONSISTENT.

properties.name: removing-aws_dx_hosted_private_virtual_interface_accepter-from-your-configuration
properties.description: » Removing aws_dx_hosted_private_virtual_interface_accepter from your configuration

AWS allows a Direct Connect hosted private virtual interface to be deleted from either the allocator's or accepter's side. However, Terraform only allows the Direct Connect hosted private virtual interface to be deleted from the allocator's side by removing the corresponding aws_dx_hosted_private_virtual_interface resource from your configuration. Removing a aws_dx_hosted_private_virtual_interface_accepter resource from your configuration will remove it from your statefile and management, but will not delete the Direct Connect virtual interface.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: address_family
properties.description: (Required) The address family for the BGP peer. ipv4 or ipv6.

properties.name: owner_account_id
properties.description: (Required) The AWS account that will own the new virtual interface.

properties.description: (Optional) The authentication key for BGP configuration.

properties.name: customer_address
properties.description: (Optional) The IPv4 CIDR destination address to which Amazon should send traffic. Required for IPv4 BGP peers.

AWS allows a Direct Connect hosted public virtual interface to be deleted from either the allocator's or accepter's side. However, Terraform only allows the Direct Connect hosted public virtual interface to be deleted from the allocator's side by removing the corresponding aws_dx_hosted_public_virtual_interface resource from your configuration. Removing a aws_dx_hosted_public_virtual_interface_accepter resource from your configuration will remove it from your statefile and management, but will not delete the Direct Connect virtual interface.

properties.name: a-note-about-attributes
properties.description: » A note about attributes
Only define attributes on the table object that are going to be used as:

properties.name: Table hash key or range key
properties.description: • Table hash key or range key

properties.name: LSI or GSI hash key or range key
properties.description: • LSI or GSI hash key or range key

The DynamoDB API expects attribute structure (name and type) to be passed along when creating or updating GSI/LSIs or creating the initial table. In these cases it expects the Hash / Range keys to be provided; because these get re-used in numerous places (i.e the table's range key could be a part of one or more GSIs), they are stored on the table object to prevent duplication and increase consistency. If you add attributes here that are not used in these scenarios it can cause an infinite loop in planning.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: table_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the table to contain the item.

properties.name: hash_key
properties.description: (Required) Hash key to use for lookups and identification of the item

properties.name: range_key
properties.description: (Optional) Range key to use for lookups and identification of the item. Required if there is range key defined in the table.

properties.name: item
properties.description: (Required) JSON representation of a map of attribute name/value pairs, one for each attribute. Only the primary key attributes are required; you can optionally provide other attribute name-value pairs for the item.

properties.description: (Required) The name of the parameter.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) The value for the parameter.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: – (Required) The name of the subnet group.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) A description of the subnet group.

properties.name: subnet_ids
properties.description: – (Required) A list of VPC subnet IDs for the subnet group.
For more detailed documentation about each argument, refer to the AWS official documentation.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: apply_immediately
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether any cluster modifications are applied immediately, or during the next maintenance window. Default is false.

properties.name: availability_zones
properties.description: (Optional) A list of EC2 Availability Zones that instances in the DB cluster can be created in.

properties.name: backup_retention_period
properties.description: (Optional) The days to retain backups for. Default 1

properties.name: cluster_identifier_prefix
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resource) Creates a unique cluster identifier beginning with the specified prefix. Conflicts with cluster_identifer.

properties.name: cluster_identifier
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resources) The cluster identifier. If omitted, Terraform will assign a random, unique identifier.

properties.name: db_subnet_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) A DB subnet group to associate with this DB instance.

properties.name: db_cluster_parameter_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) A cluster parameter group to associate with the cluster.

properties.name: enabled_cloudwatch_logs_exports
properties.description: (Optional) List of log types to export to cloudwatch. If omitted, no logs will be exported. The following log types are supported: audit.

properties.name: engine_version
properties.description: (Optional) The database engine version. Updating this argument results in an outage.

properties.name: engine
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the database engine to be used for this DB cluster. Defaults to docdb. Valid Values: docdb

properties.name: final_snapshot_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) The name of your final DB snapshot when this DB cluster is deleted. If omitted, no final snapshot will be made.

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the KMS encryption key. When specifying kms_key_id, storage_encrypted needs to be set to true.

properties.name: master_password
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier is provided) Password for the master DB user. Note that this may show up in logs, and it will be stored in the state file. Please refer to the DocDB Naming Constraints.

properties.name: master_username
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier is provided) Username for the master DB user.

properties.name: port
properties.description: (Optional) The port on which the DB accepts connections

properties.name: preferred_backup_window
properties.description: (Optional) The daily time range during which automated backups are created if automated backups are enabled using the BackupRetentionPeriod parameter.Time in UTC Default: A 30-minute window selected at random from an 8-hour block of time per region. e.g. 04:00-09:00

properties.name: skip_final_snapshot
properties.description: (Optional) Determines whether a final DB snapshot is created before the DB cluster is deleted. If true is specified, no DB snapshot is created. If false is specified, a DB snapshot is created before the DB cluster is deleted, using the value from final_snapshot_identifier. Default is false.

properties.name: snapshot_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether or not to create this cluster from a snapshot. You can use either the name or ARN when specifying a DB cluster snapshot, or the ARN when specifying a DB snapshot.

properties.name: storage_encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the DB cluster is encrypted. The default is false.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the DB cluster.

properties.name: vpc_security_group_ids
properties.description: (Optional) List of VPC security groups to associate with the Cluster
For more detailed documentation about each argument, refer to the AWS official documentation.

properties.name: apply_immediately

properties.name: name

properties.name: value

The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resource) The name of the docDB subnet group. If omitted, Terraform will assign a random, unique name.

properties.name: name_prefix
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resource) Creates a unique name beginning with the specified prefix. Conflicts with name.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The description of the docDB subnet group. Defaults to "Managed by Terraform".

properties.name: subnet_ids
properties.description: (Required) A list of VPC subnet IDs.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) A region-unique name for the AMI.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) A longer, human-readable description for the AMI.

properties.name: ena_support
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether enhanced networking with ENA is enabled. Defaults to false.

properties.name: root_device_name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the root device (for example, /dev/sda1, or /dev/xvda).

properties.name: virtualization_type
properties.description: (Optional) Keyword to choose what virtualization mode created instances will use. Can be either "paravirtual" (the default) or "hvm". The choice of virtualization type changes the set of further arguments that are required, as described below.

properties.name: architecture
properties.description: (Optional) Machine architecture for created instances. Defaults to "x86_64".

properties.name: ebs_block_device
properties.description: (Optional) Nested block describing an EBS block device that should be attached to created instances. The structure of this block is described below.

properties.name: ephemeral_block_device
properties.description: (Optional) Nested block describing an ephemeral block device that should be attached to created instances. The structure of this block is described below.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
When virtualization_type is "paravirtual" the following additional arguments apply:

properties.name: image_location
properties.description: (Required) Path to an S3 object containing an image manifest, e.g. created by the ec2-upload-bundle command in the EC2 command line tools.

properties.name: kernel_id
properties.description: (Required) The id of the kernel image (AKI) that will be used as the paravirtual kernel in created instances.

properties.name: ramdisk_id
properties.description: (Optional) The id of an initrd image (ARI) that will be used when booting the created instances.
When virtualization_type is "hvm" the following additional arguments apply:

properties.name: sriov_net_support
properties.description: (Optional) When set to "simple" (the default), enables enhanced networking for created instances. No other value is supported at this time.
Nested ebs_block_device blocks have the following structure:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: (Required) The path at which the device is exposed to created instances.

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Boolean controlling whether the EBS volumes created to support each created instance will be deleted once that instance is terminated.

properties.name: encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Boolean controlling whether the created EBS volumes will be encrypted. Can't be used with snapshot_id.

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Required only when volume_type is "io1") Number of I/O operations per second the created volumes will support.

properties.name: snapshot_id
properties.description: (Optional) The id of an EBS snapshot that will be used to initialize the created EBS volumes. If set, the volume_size attribute must be at least as large as the referenced snapshot.

properties.name: volume_size
properties.description: (Required unless snapshot_id is set) The size of created volumes in GiB. If snapshot_id is set and volume_size is omitted then the volume will have the same size as the selected snapshot.

properties.name: volume_type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of EBS volume to create. Can be one of "standard" (the default), "io1" or "gp2".

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The full ARN of the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) CMK to use when encrypting the snapshots of an image during a copy operation. This parameter is only required if you want to use a non-default CMK; if this parameter is not specified, the default CMK for EBS is used
Note: You can specify encrypted or snapshot_id but not both.
Nested ephemeral_block_device blocks have the following structure:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: (Required) The path at which the device is exposed to created instances.

properties.name: virtual_name
properties.description: (Required) A name for the ephemeral device, of the form "ephemeralN" where N is a volume number starting from zero.

properties.name: timeouts
properties.description: » Timeouts
The timeouts block allows you to specify timeouts for certain actions:

properties.name: create
properties.description: (Defaults to 40 mins) Used when creating the AMI

properties.name: update
properties.description: (Defaults to 40 mins) Used when updating the AMI

properties.name: delete
properties.description: (Defaults to 90 mins) Used when deregistering the AMI
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) A region-unique name for the AMI.

properties.name: source_ami_id
properties.description: (Required) The id of the AMI to copy. This id must be valid in the region given by source_ami_region.

properties.name: source_ami_region
properties.description: (Required) The region from which the AMI will be copied. This may be the same as the AWS provider region in order to create a copy within the same region.

properties.name: encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the destination snapshots of the copied image should be encrypted. Defaults to false

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The full ARN of the KMS Key to use when encrypting the snapshots of an image during a copy operation. If not specified, then the default AWS KMS Key will be used

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
This resource also exposes the full set of arguments from the aws_ami resource.

This is risky since it may cause a snapshot of an inconsistent filesystem state, but can be used to avoid downtime if the user otherwise guarantees that no filesystem writes will be underway at the time of snapshot.

properties.name: encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) If true, the disk will be encrypted.

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of IOPS to provision for the disk.

properties.name: size
properties.description: (Optional) The size of the drive in GiBs.

properties.name: snapshot_id

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
NOTE: When changing the size, iops or type of an instance, there are considerations to be aware of that Amazon have written about this.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: availability_zone
properties.description: (Required) The Availability Zone in which to create the Capacity Reservation.

properties.name: ebs_optimized
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether the Capacity Reservation supports EBS-optimized instances.

properties.name: end_date
properties.description: (Optional) The date and time at which the Capacity Reservation expires. When a Capacity Reservation expires, the reserved capacity is released and you can no longer launch instances into it. Valid values: RFC3339 time string (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ)

properties.name: end_date_type
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates the way in which the Capacity Reservation ends. Specify either unlimited or limited.

properties.name: ephemeral_storage
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether the Capacity Reservation supports instances with temporary, block-level storage.

properties.name: instance_count
properties.description: (Required) The number of instances for which to reserve capacity.

properties.name: instance_match_criteria
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates the type of instance launches that the Capacity Reservation accepts. Specify either open or targeted.

properties.name: instance_platform
properties.description: (Required) The type of operating system for which to reserve capacity. Valid options are Linux/UNIX, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux, Windows, Windows with SQL Server, Windows with SQL Server Enterprise, Windows with SQL Server Standard or Windows with SQL Server Web.

properties.name: instance_type
properties.description: (Required) The instance type for which to reserve capacity.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: tenancy
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates the tenancy of the Capacity Reservation. Specify either default or dedicated.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the repository.

properties.name: client_cidr_block
properties.description: (Required) The IPv4 address range, in CIDR notation, from which to assign client IP addresses. The address range cannot overlap with the local CIDR of the VPC in which the associated subnet is located, or the routes that you add manually. The address range cannot be changed after the Client VPN endpoint has been created. The CIDR block should be /22 or greater.

properties.name: dns_servers
properties.description: (Optional) Information about the DNS servers to be used for DNS resolution. A Client VPN endpoint can have up to two DNS servers. If no DNS server is specified, the DNS address of the VPC that is to be associated with Client VPN endpoint is used as the DNS server.

properties.name: server_certificate_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the ACM server certificate.

properties.name: transport_protocol
properties.description: (Optional) The transport protocol to be used by the VPN session. Default value is udp.

properties.name: authentication_options
properties.description: (Required) Information about the authentication method to be used to authenticate clients.

properties.name: connection_log_options
properties.description: (Required) Information about the client connection logging options.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: authentication_options-argument-reference
properties.description: » authentication_options Argument Reference
One of the following arguments must be supplied:

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of client authentication to be used. Specify certificate-authentication to use certificate-based authentication, or directory-service-authentication to use Active Directory authentication.

properties.name: active_directory_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the Active Directory to be used for authentication if type is directory-service-authentication.

properties.name: root_certificate_chain_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN of the client certificate. The certificate must be signed by a certificate authority (CA) and it must be provisioned in AWS Certificate Manager (ACM). Only necessary when type is set to certificate-authentication.

properties.name: connection_log_options-argument-reference
properties.description: » connection_log_options Argument Reference
One of the following arguments must be supplied:

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Required) Indicates whether connection logging is enabled.

properties.name: cloudwatch_log_group
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the CloudWatch Logs log group.

properties.name: cloudwatch_log_stream
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the CloudWatch Logs log stream to which the connection data is published.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: client_vpn_endpoint_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the Client VPN endpoint.

properties.name: subnet_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the subnet to associate with the Client VPN endpoint.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: launch_template_config
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument containing EC2 Launch Template configurations. Defined below.

properties.name: target_capacity_specification
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument containing target capacity configurations. Defined below.

properties.name: excess_capacity_termination_policy
properties.description: (Optional) Whether running instances should be terminated if the total target capacity of the EC2 Fleet is decreased below the current size of the EC2. Valid values: no-termination, termination. Defaults to termination.

properties.name: on_demand_options
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument containing On-Demand configurations. Defined below.

properties.name: replace_unhealthy_instances
properties.description: (Optional) Whether EC2 Fleet should replace unhealthy instances. Defaults to false.

properties.name: spot_options
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument containing Spot configurations. Defined below.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Map of Fleet tags. To tag instances at launch, specify the tags in the Launch Template.

properties.name: terminate_instances
properties.description: (Optional) Whether to terminate instances for an EC2 Fleet if it is deleted successfully. Defaults to false.

properties.name: terminate_instances_with_expiration
properties.description: (Optional) Whether running instances should be terminated when the EC2 Fleet expires. Defaults to false.

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of request. Indicates whether the EC2 Fleet only requests the target capacity, or also attempts to maintain it. Valid values: maintain, request. Defaults to maintain.

properties.name: launch_template_config-1
properties.description: » launch_template_config

properties.name: launch_template_specification
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument containing EC2 Launch Template to use. Defined below.

properties.name: override
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument(s) containing parameters to override the same parameters in the Launch Template. Defined below.

properties.name: launch_template_specification-1
properties.description: » launch_template_specification
NOTE: Either launch_template_id or launch_template_name must be specified.

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Required) Version number of the launch template.

properties.name: launch_template_id
properties.description: (Optional) ID of the launch template.

properties.name: launch_template_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the launch template.

properties.name: override-1
properties.description: » override
Example:

resource "aws_ec2_fleet" "example" {
  # ... other configuration ...

  launch_template_config {
    # ... other configuration ...

    override {
      instance_type     = "m4.xlarge"
      weighted_capacity = 1
    }

    override {
      instance_type     = "m4.2xlarge"
      weighted_capacity = 2
    }
  }
}

properties.name: availability_zone
properties.description: (Optional) Availability Zone in which to launch the instances.

properties.name: instance_type
properties.description: (Optional) Instance type.

properties.name: max_price
properties.description: (Optional) Maximum price per unit hour that you are willing to pay for a Spot Instance.

properties.name: priority
properties.description: (Optional) Priority for the launch template override. If on_demand_options allocation_strategy is set to prioritized, EC2 Fleet uses priority to determine which launch template override to use first in fulfilling On-Demand capacity. The highest priority is launched first. The lower the number, the higher the priority. If no number is set, the launch template override has the lowest priority. Valid values are whole numbers starting at 0.

properties.name: subnet_id
properties.description: (Optional) ID of the subnet in which to launch the instances.

properties.name: weighted_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) Number of units provided by the specified instance type.

properties.name: on_demand_options-1
properties.description: » on_demand_options

properties.name: allocation_strategy
properties.description: (Optional) The order of the launch template overrides to use in fulfilling On-Demand capacity. Valid values: lowestPrice, prioritized. Default: lowestPrice.

properties.name: spot_options-1
properties.description: » spot_options

properties.name: allocation_strategy
properties.description: (Optional) How to allocate the target capacity across the Spot pools. Valid values: diversified, lowestPrice. Default: lowestPrice.

properties.name: instance_interruption_behavior
properties.description: (Optional) Behavior when a Spot Instance is interrupted. Valid values: hibernate, stop, terminate. Default: terminate.

properties.name: instance_pools_to_use_count
properties.description: (Optional) Number of Spot pools across which to allocate your target Spot capacity. Valid only when Spot allocation_strategy is set to lowestPrice. Default: 1.

properties.name: target_capacity_specification-1
properties.description: » target_capacity_specification

properties.name: default_target_capacity_type
properties.description: (Required) Default target capacity type. Valid values: on-demand, spot.

properties.name: total_target_capacity
properties.description: (Required) The number of units to request, filled using default_target_capacity_type.

properties.name: on_demand_target_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) The number of On-Demand units to request.

properties.name: spot_target_capacity
properties.description: (Optional) The number of Spot units to request.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: amazon_side_asn
properties.description: (Optional) Private Autonomous System Number (ASN) for the Amazon side of a BGP session. The range is 64512 to 65534 for 16-bit ASNs and 4200000000 to 4294967294 for 32-bit ASNs. Default value: 64512.

properties.name: auto_accept_shared_attachments
properties.description: (Optional) Whether resource attachment requests are automatically accepted. Valid values: disable, enable. Default value: disable.

properties.name: default_route_table_association
properties.description: (Optional) Whether resource attachments are automatically associated with the default association route table. Valid values: disable, enable. Default value: enable.

properties.name: default_route_table_propagation
properties.description: (Optional) Whether resource attachments automatically propagate routes to the default propagation route table. Valid values: disable, enable. Default value: enable.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Description of the EC2 Transit Gateway.

properties.name: dns_support
properties.description: (Optional) Whether DNS support is enabled. Valid values: disable, enable. Default value: enable.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value tags for the EC2 Transit Gateway.

properties.name: vpn_ecmp_support
properties.description: (Optional) Whether VPN Equal Cost Multipath Protocol support is enabled. Valid values: disable, enable. Default value: enable.

properties.name: destination_cidr_block

properties.name: transit_gateway_attachment_id

properties.name: blackhole

properties.name: transit_gateway_route_table_id

properties.name: transit_gateway_id

properties.name: transit_gateway_attachment_id

properties.name: transit_gateway_route_table_id
properties.description: (Required) Identifier of EC2 Transit Gateway Route Table.

properties.name: transit_gateway_attachment_id

properties.name: update

properties.name: block-devices
properties.description: » Block devices

Each of the *_block_device attributes control a portion of the AWS Instance's "Block Device Mapping". It's a good idea to familiarize yourself with AWS's Block Device Mapping docs to understand the implications of using these attributes.
The root_block_device mapping supports the following:

properties.name: volume_type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of volume. Can be "standard", "gp2", "io1", "sc1", or "st1". (Default: "standard").

properties.name: volume_size
properties.description: (Optional) The size of the volume in gibibytes (GiB).

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of provisioned IOPS. This is only valid for volume_type of "io1", and must be specified if using that type

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the volume should be destroyed on instance termination (Default: true).
Modifying any of the root_block_device settings requires resource replacement.
Each ebs_block_device supports the following:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: The name of the device to mount.

properties.name: snapshot_id
properties.description: (Optional) The Snapshot ID to mount.

properties.name: volume_type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of volume. Can be "standard", "gp2", or "io1". (Default: "standard").

properties.name: volume_size
properties.description: (Optional) The size of the volume in gibibytes (GiB).

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of provisioned IOPS. This must be set with a volume_type of "io1".

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the volume should be destroyed on instance termination (Default: true).

properties.name: encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Enables EBS encryption on the volume (Default: false). Cannot be used with snapshot_id.

NOTE: Currently, changes to the ebs_block_device configuration of existing resources cannot be automatically detected by Terraform. To manage changes and attachments of an EBS block to an instance, use the aws_ebs_volume and aws_volume_attachment resources instead. If you use ebs_block_device on an aws_instance, Terraform will assume management over the full set of non-root EBS block devices for the instance, treating additional block devices as drift. For this reason, ebs_block_device cannot be mixed with external aws_ebs_volume and aws_volume_attachment resources for a given instance.
Each ephemeral_block_device supports the following:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: The name of the block device to mount on the instance.

properties.name: virtual_name
properties.description: (Optional) The Instance Store Device Name (e.g. "ephemeral0").

properties.name: no_device
properties.description: (Optional) Suppresses the specified device included in the AMI's block device mapping.

Each AWS Instance type has a different set of Instance Store block devices available for attachment. AWS publishes a list of which ephemeral devices are available on each type. The devices are always identified by the virtual_name in the format "ephemeral{0..N}".

properties.name: network-interfaces
properties.description: » Network Interfaces

Each of the network_interface blocks attach a network interface to an EC2 Instance during boot time. However, because the network interface is attached at boot-time, replacing/modifying the network interface WILL trigger a recreation of the EC2 Instance. If you should need at any point to detach/modify/re-attach a network interface to the instance, use the aws_network_interface or aws_network_interface_attachment resources instead.
The network_interface configuration block does, however, allow users to supply their own network interface to be used as the default network interface on an EC2 Instance, attached at eth0.
Each network_interface block supports the following:

properties.name: device_index
properties.description: (Required) The integer index of the network interface attachment. Limited by instance type.

properties.name: network_interface_id
properties.description: (Required) The ID of the network interface to attach.

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Whether or not to delete the network interface on instance termination. Defaults to false. Currently, the only valid value is false, as this is only supported when creating new network interfaces when launching an instance.

properties.name: credit-specification
properties.description: » Credit Specification
NOTE: Removing this configuration on existing instances will only stop managing it. It will not change the configuration back to the default for the instance type.
Credit specification can be applied/modified to the EC2 Instance at any time.
The credit_specification block supports the following:

properties.name: cpu_credits
properties.description: (Optional) The credit option for CPU usage. Can be "standard" or "unlimited". T3 instances are launched as unlimited by default. T2 instances are launched as standard by default.

properties.name: example
properties.description: » Example

resource "aws_vpc" "my_vpc" {
  cidr_block = "172.16.0.0/16"

  tags = {
    Name = "tf-example"
  }
}

resource "aws_subnet" "my_subnet" {
  vpc_id            = "${aws_vpc.my_vpc.id}"
  cidr_block        = "172.16.10.0/24"
  availability_zone = "us-west-2a"

  tags = {
    Name = "tf-example"
  }
}

resource "aws_network_interface" "foo" {
  subnet_id   = "${aws_subnet.my_subnet.id}"
  private_ips = ["172.16.10.100"]

  tags = {
    Name = "primary_network_interface"
  }
}

resource "aws_instance" "foo" {
  ami           = "ami-22b9a343" # us-west-2
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  network_interface {
    network_interface_id = "${aws_network_interface.foo.id}"
    device_index         = 0
  }

  credit_specification {
    cpu_credits = "unlimited"
  }
}
