properties.description: (Required) Path to the top-level parent that contains the records.

properties.name: s3-reference
properties.description: » S3 Reference
Identifies the S3 bucket and object that contains the reference data.
The s3 blcok supports the following:

properties.name: bucket_arn
properties.description: (Required) The S3 Bucket ARN.

properties.name: file_key
properties.description: (Required) The File Key name containing reference data.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The IAM Role ARN to read the data.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) A name to identify the stream. This is unique to the AWS account and region the Stream is created in.

properties.name: shard_count
properties.description: – (Required) The number of shards that the stream will use. Amazon has guidelines for specifying the Stream size that should be referenced when creating a Kinesis stream. See Amazon Kinesis Streams for more.

properties.name: retention_period
properties.description: (Optional) Length of time data records are accessible after they are added to the stream. The maximum value of a stream's retention period is 168 hours. Minimum value is 24. Default is 24.

properties.name: shard_level_metrics
properties.description: (Optional) A list of shard-level CloudWatch metrics which can be enabled for the stream. See Monitoring with CloudWatch for more. Note that the value ALL should not be used; instead you should provide an explicit list of metrics you wish to enable.

properties.name: enforce_consumer_deletion
properties.description: (Optional) A boolean that indicates all registered consumers should be deregistered from the stream so that the stream can be destroyed without error. The default value is false.

properties.name: encryption_type
properties.description: (Optional) The encryption type to use. The only acceptable values are NONE or KMS. The default value is NONE.

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The GUID for the customer-managed KMS key to use for encryption. You can also use a Kinesis-owned master key by specifying the alias alias/aws/kinesis.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) A name to identify the stream. This is unique to the AWS account and region the Stream is created in.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: kinesis_source_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Allows the ability to specify the kinesis stream that is used as the source of the firehose delivery stream.

properties.name: destination
properties.description: – (Required) This is the destination to where the data is delivered. The only options are s3 (Deprecated, use extended_s3 instead), extended_s3, redshift, elasticsearch, and splunk.

properties.name: s3_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Required for non-S3 destinations. For S3 destination, use extended_s3_configuration instead. Configuration options for the s3 destination (or the intermediate bucket if the destination is redshift). More details are given below.

properties.name: extended_s3_configuration
properties.description: (Optional, only Required when destination is extended_s3) Enhanced configuration options for the s3 destination. More details are given below.

properties.name: redshift_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Configuration options if redshift is the destination. Using redshift_configuration requires the user to also specify a s3_configuration block. More details are given below.
The kinesis_source_configuration object supports the following:

properties.name: kinesis_stream_arn
properties.description: (Required) The kinesis stream used as the source of the firehose delivery stream.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the role that provides access to the source Kinesis stream.
The s3_configuration object supports the following:

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the AWS credentials.

properties.name: bucket_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the S3 bucket

properties.name: prefix
properties.description: (Optional) The "YYYY/MM/DD/HH" time format prefix is automatically used for delivered S3 files. You can specify an extra prefix to be added in front of the time format prefix. Note that if the prefix ends with a slash, it appears as a folder in the S3 bucket

properties.name: buffer_size
properties.description: (Optional) Buffer incoming data to the specified size, in MBs, before delivering it to the destination. The default value is 5. We recommend setting SizeInMBs to a value greater than the amount of data you typically ingest into the delivery stream in 10 seconds. For example, if you typically ingest data at 1 MB/sec set SizeInMBs to be 10 MB or higher.

properties.name: buffer_interval
properties.description: (Optional) Buffer incoming data for the specified period of time, in seconds, before delivering it to the destination. The default value is 300.

properties.name: compression_format
properties.description: (Optional) The compression format. If no value is specified, the default is UNCOMPRESSED. Other supported values are GZIP, ZIP & Snappy. If the destination is redshift you cannot use ZIP or Snappy.

properties.name: kms_key_arn
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the KMS key ARN the stream will use to encrypt data. If not set, no encryption will be used.

properties.name: cloudwatch_logging_options
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch Logging Options for the delivery stream. More details are given below
The extended_s3_configuration object supports the same fields from s3_configuration as well as the following:

properties.name: data_format_conversion_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument for the serializer, deserializer, and schema for converting data from the JSON format to the Parquet or ORC format before writing it to Amazon S3. More details given below.

properties.name: error_output_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) Prefix added to failed records before writing them to S3. This prefix appears immediately following the bucket name.

properties.name: processing_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The data processing configuration. More details are given below.

properties.name: s3_backup_mode
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon S3 backup mode. Valid values are Disabled and Enabled. Default value is Disabled.

properties.name: s3_backup_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The configuration for backup in Amazon S3. Required if s3_backup_mode is Enabled. Supports the same fields as s3_configuration object.
The redshift_configuration object supports the following:

properties.name: cluster_jdbcurl
properties.description: (Required) The jdbcurl of the redshift cluster.

properties.name: username
properties.description: (Required) The username that the firehose delivery stream will assume. It is strongly recommended that the username and password provided is used exclusively for Amazon Kinesis Firehose purposes, and that the permissions for the account are restricted for Amazon Redshift INSERT permissions.

properties.name: password
properties.description: (Required) The password for the username above.

properties.name: retry_duration
properties.description: (Optional) The length of time during which Firehose retries delivery after a failure, starting from the initial request and including the first attempt. The default value is 3600 seconds (60 minutes). Firehose does not retry if the value of DurationInSeconds is 0 (zero) or if the first delivery attempt takes longer than the current value.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The arn of the role the stream assumes.

properties.name: s3_backup_mode
properties.description: (Optional) The Amazon S3 backup mode. Valid values are Disabled and Enabled. Default value is Disabled.

properties.name: s3_backup_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The configuration for backup in Amazon S3. Required if s3_backup_mode is Enabled. Supports the same fields as s3_configuration object.

properties.name: data_table_name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the table in the redshift cluster that the s3 bucket will copy to.

properties.name: copy_options
properties.description: (Optional) Copy options for copying the data from the s3 intermediate bucket into redshift, for example to change the default delimiter. For valid values, see the AWS documentation

properties.name: data_table_columns
properties.description: (Optional) The data table columns that will be targeted by the copy command.

properties.name: cloudwatch_logging_options
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch Logging Options for the delivery stream. More details are given below

properties.name: processing_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The data processing configuration. More details are given below.
The elasticsearch_configuration object supports the following:

properties.name: buffering_interval
properties.description: (Optional) Buffer incoming data for the specified period of time, in seconds between 60 to 900, before delivering it to the destination. The default value is 300s.

properties.name: buffering_size
properties.description: (Optional) Buffer incoming data to the specified size, in MBs between 1 to 100, before delivering it to the destination. The default value is 5MB.

properties.name: domain_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the Amazon ES domain. The IAM role must have permission for DescribeElasticsearchDomain, DescribeElasticsearchDomains, and DescribeElasticsearchDomainConfig after assuming RoleARN. The pattern needs to be arn:.*.

properties.name: index_name
properties.description: (Required) The Elasticsearch index name.

properties.name: index_rotation_period
properties.description: (Optional) The Elasticsearch index rotation period. Index rotation appends a timestamp to the IndexName to facilitate expiration of old data. Valid values are NoRotation, OneHour, OneDay, OneWeek, and OneMonth. The default value is OneDay.

properties.name: retry_duration
properties.description: (Optional) After an initial failure to deliver to Amazon Elasticsearch, the total amount of time, in seconds between 0 to 7200, during which Firehose re-attempts delivery (including the first attempt). After this time has elapsed, the failed documents are written to Amazon S3. The default value is 300s. There will be no retry if the value is 0.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of the IAM role to be assumed by Firehose for calling the Amazon ES Configuration API and for indexing documents. The pattern needs to be arn:.*.

properties.name: s3_backup_mode
properties.description: (Optional) Defines how documents should be delivered to Amazon S3. Valid values are FailedDocumentsOnly and AllDocuments. Default value is FailedDocumentsOnly.

properties.name: type_name
properties.description: (Required) The Elasticsearch type name with maximum length of 100 characters.

properties.name: cloudwatch_logging_options
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch Logging Options for the delivery stream. More details are given below

properties.name: processing_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The data processing configuration. More details are given below.
The splunk_configuration objects supports the following:

properties.name: hec_acknowledgment_timeout
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time, in seconds between 180 and 600, that Kinesis Firehose waits to receive an acknowledgment from Splunk after it sends it data.

properties.name: hec_endpoint
properties.description: (Required) The HTTP Event Collector (HEC) endpoint to which Kinesis Firehose sends your data.

properties.name: hec_endpoint_type
properties.description: (Optional) The HEC endpoint type. Valid values are Raw or Event. The default value is Raw.

properties.name: hec_token
properties.description: The GUID that you obtain from your Splunk cluster when you create a new HEC endpoint.

properties.name: s3_backup_mode
properties.description: (Optional) Defines how documents should be delivered to Amazon S3. Valid values are FailedEventsOnly and AllEvents. Default value is FailedEventsOnly.

properties.name: retry_duration
properties.description: (Optional) After an initial failure to deliver to Amazon Elasticsearch, the total amount of time, in seconds between 0 to 7200, during which Firehose re-attempts delivery (including the first attempt). After this time has elapsed, the failed documents are written to Amazon S3. The default value is 300s. There will be no retry if the value is 0.

properties.name: cloudwatch_logging_options
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch Logging Options for the delivery stream. More details are given below.

properties.name: processing_configuration
properties.description: (Optional) The data processing configuration. More details are given below.
The cloudwatch_logging_options object supports the following:

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Enables or disables the logging. Defaults to false.

properties.name: log_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch group name for logging. This value is required if enabled is true.

properties.name: log_stream_name
properties.description: (Optional) The CloudWatch log stream name for logging. This value is required if enabled is true.
The processing_configuration object supports the following:

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Enables or disables data processing.

properties.name: processors
properties.description: (Optional) Array of data processors. More details are given below
The processors array objects support the following:

properties.name: type
properties.description: (Required) The type of processor. Valid Values: Lambda

properties.name: parameters
properties.description: (Optional) Array of processor parameters. More details are given below
The parameters array objects support the following:

properties.name: parameter_name
properties.description: (Required) Parameter name. Valid Values: LambdaArn, NumberOfRetries, RoleArn, BufferSizeInMBs, BufferIntervalInSeconds

properties.name: parameter_value
properties.description: (Required) Parameter value. Must be between 1 and 512 length (inclusive). When providing a Lambda ARN, you should specify the resource version as well.

properties.name: data_format_conversion_configuration-1
properties.description: » data_format_conversion_configuration
Example:

resource "aws_kinesis_firehose_delivery_stream" "example" {
  # ... other configuration ...
  extended_s3_configuration {
    # Must be at least 64
    buffer_size = 128

    # ... other configuration ...
    data_format_conversion_configuration {
      input_format_configuration {
        deserializer {
          hive_json_ser_de {}
        }
      }

      output_format_configuration {
        serializer {
          orc_ser_de {}
        }
      }

      schema_configuration {
        database_name = "${aws_glue_catalog_table.example.database_name}"
        role_arn      = "${aws_iam_role.example.arn}"
        table_name    = "${aws_glue_catalog_table.example.name}"
      }
    }
  }
}

properties.name: input_format_configuration
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that specifies the deserializer that you want Kinesis Data Firehose to use to convert the format of your data from JSON. More details below.

properties.name: output_format_configuration
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that specifies the serializer that you want Kinesis Data Firehose to use to convert the format of your data to the Parquet or ORC format. More details below.

properties.name: schema_configuration
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that specifies the AWS Glue Data Catalog table that contains the column information. More details below.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Defaults to true. Set it to false if you want to disable format conversion while preserving the configuration details.

properties.name: input_format_configuration-1
properties.description: » input_format_configuration

properties.name: deserializer
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that specifies which deserializer to use. You can choose either the Apache Hive JSON SerDe or the OpenX JSON SerDe. More details below.

properties.name: deserializer-1
properties.description: » deserializer
NOTE: One of the deserializers must be configured. If no nested configuration needs to occur simply declare as XXX_json_ser_de = [] or XXX_json_ser_de {}.

properties.name: hive_json_ser_de
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument that specifies the native Hive / HCatalog JsonSerDe. More details below.

properties.name: open_x_json_ser_de
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument that specifies the OpenX SerDe. More details below.

properties.name: hive_json_ser_de-1
properties.description: » hive_json_ser_de

properties.name: timestamp_formats
properties.description: (Optional) A list of how you want Kinesis Data Firehose to parse the date and time stamps that may be present in your input data JSON. To specify these format strings, follow the pattern syntax of JodaTime's DateTimeFormat format strings. For more information, see Class DateTimeFormat. You can also use the special value millis to parse time stamps in epoch milliseconds. If you don't specify a format, Kinesis Data Firehose uses java.sql.Timestamp::valueOf by default.

properties.name: open_x_json_ser_de-1
properties.description: » open_x_json_ser_de

properties.name: case_insensitive
properties.description: (Optional) When set to true, which is the default, Kinesis Data Firehose converts JSON keys to lowercase before deserializing them.

properties.name: column_to_json_key_mappings
properties.description: (Optional) A map of column names to JSON keys that aren't identical to the column names. This is useful when the JSON contains keys that are Hive keywords. For example, timestamp is a Hive keyword. If you have a JSON key named timestamp, set this parameter to { ts = "timestamp" } to map this key to a column named ts.

properties.name: convert_dots_in_json_keys_to_underscores
properties.description: (Optional) When set to true, specifies that the names of the keys include dots and that you want Kinesis Data Firehose to replace them with underscores. This is useful because Apache Hive does not allow dots in column names. For example, if the JSON contains a key whose name is "a.b", you can define the column name to be "a_b" when using this option. Defaults to false.

properties.name: output_format_configuration-1
properties.description: » output_format_configuration

properties.name: serializer
properties.description: (Required) Nested argument that specifies which serializer to use. You can choose either the ORC SerDe or the Parquet SerDe. More details below.

properties.name: serializer-1
properties.description: » serializer
NOTE: One of the serializers must be configured. If no nested configuration needs to occur simply declare as XXX_ser_de = [] or XXX_ser_de {}.

properties.name: orc_ser_de
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument that specifies converting data to the ORC format before storing it in Amazon S3. For more information, see Apache ORC. More details below.

properties.name: parquet_ser_de
properties.description: (Optional) Nested argument that specifies converting data to the Parquet format before storing it in Amazon S3. For more information, see Apache Parquet. More details below.

properties.name: orc_ser_de-1
properties.description: » orc_ser_de

properties.name: block_size_bytes
properties.description: (Optional) The Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) block size. This is useful if you intend to copy the data from Amazon S3 to HDFS before querying. The default is 256 MiB and the minimum is 64 MiB. Kinesis Data Firehose uses this value for padding calculations.

properties.name: bloom_filter_columns
properties.description: (Optional) A list of column names for which you want Kinesis Data Firehose to create bloom filters.

properties.name: bloom_filter_false_positive_probability
properties.description: (Optional) The Bloom filter false positive probability (FPP). The lower the FPP, the bigger the Bloom filter. The default value is 0.05, the minimum is 0, and the maximum is 1.

properties.name: compression
properties.description: (Optional) The compression code to use over data blocks. The default is SNAPPY.

properties.name: dictionary_key_threshold
properties.description: (Optional) A float that represents the fraction of the total number of non-null rows. To turn off dictionary encoding, set this fraction to a number that is less than the number of distinct keys in a dictionary. To always use dictionary encoding, set this threshold to 1.

properties.name: enable_padding
properties.description: (Optional) Set this to true to indicate that you want stripes to be padded to the HDFS block boundaries. This is useful if you intend to copy the data from Amazon S3 to HDFS before querying. The default is false.

properties.name: format_version
properties.description: (Optional) The version of the file to write. The possible values are V0_11 and V0_12. The default is V0_12.

properties.name: padding_tolerance
properties.description: (Optional) A float between 0 and 1 that defines the tolerance for block padding as a decimal fraction of stripe size. The default value is 0.05, which means 5 percent of stripe size. For the default values of 64 MiB ORC stripes and 256 MiB HDFS blocks, the default block padding tolerance of 5 percent reserves a maximum of 3.2 MiB for padding within the 256 MiB block. In such a case, if the available size within the block is more than 3.2 MiB, a new, smaller stripe is inserted to fit within that space. This ensures that no stripe crosses block boundaries and causes remote reads within a node-local task. Kinesis Data Firehose ignores this parameter when enable_padding is false.

properties.name: row_index_stride
properties.description: (Optional) The number of rows between index entries. The default is 10000 and the minimum is 1000.

properties.name: stripe_size_bytes
properties.description: (Optional) The number of bytes in each stripe. The default is 64 MiB and the minimum is 8 MiB.

properties.name: parquet_ser_de-1
properties.description: » parquet_ser_de

properties.name: block_size_bytes
properties.description: (Optional) The Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) block size. This is useful if you intend to copy the data from Amazon S3 to HDFS before querying. The default is 256 MiB and the minimum is 64 MiB. Kinesis Data Firehose uses this value for padding calculations.

properties.name: compression
properties.description: (Optional) The compression code to use over data blocks. The possible values are UNCOMPRESSED, SNAPPY, and GZIP, with the default being SNAPPY. Use SNAPPY for higher decompression speed. Use GZIP if the compression ratio is more important than speed.

properties.name: enable_dictionary_compression
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates whether to enable dictionary compression.

properties.name: max_padding_bytes
properties.description: (Optional) The maximum amount of padding to apply. This is useful if you intend to copy the data from Amazon S3 to HDFS before querying. The default is 0.

properties.name: page_size_bytes
properties.description: (Optional) The Parquet page size. Column chunks are divided into pages. A page is conceptually an indivisible unit (in terms of compression and encoding). The minimum value is 64 KiB and the default is 1 MiB.

properties.name: writer_version
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates the version of row format to output. The possible values are V1 and V2. The default is V1.

properties.name: schema_configuration-1
properties.description: » schema_configuration

properties.name: database_name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the AWS Glue database that contains the schema for the output data.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) The role that Kinesis Data Firehose can use to access AWS Glue. This role must be in the same account you use for Kinesis Data Firehose. Cross-account roles aren't allowed.

properties.name: table_name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the AWS Glue table that contains the column information that constitutes your data schema.

properties.name: catalog_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the AWS Glue Data Catalog. If you don't supply this, the AWS account ID is used by default.

properties.name: region
properties.description: (Optional) If you don't specify an AWS Region, the default is the current region.

properties.name: version_id
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the table version for the output data schema. Defaults to LATEST.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The display name of the alias. The name must start with the word "alias" followed by a forward slash (alias/)

properties.name: name_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) Creates an unique alias beginning with the specified prefix. The name must start with the word "alias" followed by a forward slash (alias/). Conflicts with name.

properties.name: target_key_id
properties.description: (Required) Identifier for the key for which the alias is for, can be either an ARN or key_id.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: deletion_window_in_days
properties.description: (Optional) Duration in days after which the key is deleted after destruction of the resource. Must be between 7 and 30 days. Defaults to 30.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Description of the key.

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the key is enabled. Keys pending import can only be false. Imported keys default to true unless expired.

properties.name: key_material_base64
properties.description: (Optional) Base64 encoded 256-bit symmetric encryption key material to import. The CMK is permanently associated with this key material. The same key material can be reimported, but you cannot import different key material.

properties.name: policy
properties.description: (Optional) A key policy JSON document. If you do not provide a key policy, AWS KMS attaches a default key policy to the CMK.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A key-value map of tags to assign to the key.

properties.name: valid_to
properties.description: (Optional) Time at which the imported key material expires. When the key material expires, AWS KMS deletes the key material and the CMK becomes unusable. If not specified, key material does not expire. Valid values: RFC3339 time string (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ)
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resources) A friendly name for identifying the grant.

properties.name: key_id
properties.description: (Required, Forces new resources) The unique identifier for the customer master key (CMK) that the grant applies to. Specify the key ID or the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the CMK. To specify a CMK in a different AWS account, you must use the key ARN.

properties.name: grantee_principal
properties.description: (Required, Forces new resources) The principal that is given permission to perform the operations that the grant permits in ARN format. Note that due to eventual consistency issues around IAM principals, terraform's state may not always be refreshed to reflect what is true in AWS.

properties.name: operations
properties.description: (Required, Forces new resources) A list of operations that the grant permits. The permitted values are: Decrypt, Encrypt, GenerateDataKey, GenerateDataKeyWithoutPlaintext, ReEncryptFrom, ReEncryptTo, CreateGrant, RetireGrant, DescribeKey

properties.name: retiree_principal
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resources) The principal that is given permission to retire the grant by using RetireGrant operation in ARN format. Note that due to eventual consistency issues around IAM principals, terraform's state may not always be refreshed to reflect what is true in AWS.

properties.name: constraints
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resources) A structure that you can use to allow certain operations in the grant only when the desired encryption context is present. For more information about encryption context, see Encryption Context.

properties.name: grant_creation_tokens
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resources) A list of grant tokens to be used when creating the grant. See Grant Tokens for more information about grant tokens.

properties.name: retire_on_delete
properties.description: -(Defaults to false, Forces new resources) If set to false (the default) the grants will be revoked upon deletion, and if set to true the grants will try to be retired upon deletion. Note that retiring grants requires special permissions, hence why we default to revoking grants. See RetireGrant for more information.
The constraints block supports the following arguments:

properties.name: encryption_context_equals
properties.description: (Optional) A list of key-value pairs that must match the encryption context in subsequent cryptographic operation requests. The grant allows the operation only when the encryption context in the request is the same as the encryption context specified in this constraint. Conflicts with encryption_context_subset.

properties.name: encryption_context_subset
properties.description: (Optional) A list of key-value pairs that must be included in the encryption context of subsequent cryptographic operation requests. The grant allows the cryptographic operation only when the encryption context in the request includes the key-value pairs specified in this constraint, although it can include additional key-value pairs. Conflicts with encryption_context_equals.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: plaintext
properties.description: (Required) Data to be encrypted. Note that this may show up in logs, and it will be stored in the state file.

properties.name: key_id
properties.description: (Required) Globally unique key ID for the customer master key.

properties.name: context
properties.description: (Optional) An optional mapping that makes up the encryption context.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The description of the key as viewed in AWS console.

properties.name: key_usage
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies the intended use of the key. Defaults to ENCRYPT_DECRYPT, and only symmetric encryption and decryption are supported.

properties.name: policy
properties.description: (Optional) A valid policy JSON document. For more information about building AWS IAM policy documents with Terraform, see the AWS IAM Policy Document Guide.

properties.name: deletion_window_in_days
properties.description: (Optional) Duration in days after which the key is deleted after destruction of the resource, must be between 7 and 30 days. Defaults to 30 days.

properties.name: is_enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the key is enabled. Defaults to true.

properties.name: enable_key_rotation
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether key rotation is enabled. Defaults to false.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the object.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) Name for the alias you are creating. Pattern: (?!^[0-9]+$)([a-zA-Z0-9-_]+)

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Description of the alias.

properties.name: function_name
properties.description: (Required) The function ARN of the Lambda function for which you want to create an alias.

properties.name: function_version
properties.description: (Required) Lambda function version for which you are creating the alias. Pattern: (\$LATEST|[0-9]+).

properties.name: routing_config
properties.description: (Optional) The Lambda alias' route configuration settings. Fields documented below
For routing_config the following attributes are supported:

properties.name: additional_version_weights
properties.description: (Optional) A map that defines the proportion of events that should be sent to different versions of a lambda function.

properties.name: batch_size
properties.description: (Optional) The largest number of records that Lambda will retrieve from your event source at the time of invocation. Defaults to 100 for DynamoDB and Kinesis, 10 for SQS.

properties.name: event_source_arn
properties.description: (Required) The event source ARN

properties.name: enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Determines if the mapping will be enabled on creation. Defaults to true.

properties.name: function_name
properties.description: (Required) The name or the ARN of the Lambda function that will be subscribing to events.

properties.name: starting_position
properties.description: (Optional) The position in the stream where AWS Lambda should start reading. Must be one of AT_TIMESTAMP (Kinesis only), LATEST or TRIM_HORIZON if getting events from Kinesis or DynamoDB. Must not be provided if getting events from SQS. More information about these positions can be found in the AWS DynamoDB Streams API Reference and AWS Kinesis API Reference.

properties.name: starting_position_timestamp
properties.description: (Optional) A timestamp in RFC3339 format of the data record which to start reading when using starting_position set to AT_TIMESTAMP. If a record with this exact timestamp does not exist, the next later record is chosen. If the timestamp is older than the current trim horizon, the oldest available record is chosen.

properties.name: filename
properties.description: (Optional) The path to the function's deployment package within the local filesystem. If defined, The s3_-prefixed options cannot be used.

properties.name: s3_bucket
properties.description: (Optional) The S3 bucket location containing the function's deployment package. Conflicts with filename. This bucket must reside in the same AWS region where you are creating the Lambda function.

properties.name: s3_key
properties.description: (Optional) The S3 key of an object containing the function's deployment package. Conflicts with filename.

properties.name: s3_object_version
properties.description: (Optional) The object version containing the function's deployment package. Conflicts with filename.

properties.name: function_name
properties.description: (Required) A unique name for your Lambda Function.

properties.description: (Optional) Nested block to configure the function's dead letter queue. See details below.

properties.name: handler
properties.description: (Required) The function entrypoint in your code.

properties.name: role
properties.description: (Required) IAM role attached to the Lambda Function. This governs both who / what can invoke your Lambda Function, as well as what resources our Lambda Function has access to. See Lambda Permission Model for more details.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) Description of what your Lambda Function does.

properties.name: layers
properties.description: (Optional) List of Lambda Layer Version ARNs (maximum of 5) to attach to your Lambda Function. See Lambda Layers

properties.name: memory_size
properties.description: (Optional) Amount of memory in MB your Lambda Function can use at runtime. Defaults to 128. See Limits

properties.name: runtime
properties.description: (Required) See Runtimes for valid values.

properties.name: timeout
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time your Lambda Function has to run in seconds. Defaults to 3. See Limits

properties.name: reserved_concurrent_executions
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of reserved concurrent executions for this lambda function. A value of 0 disables lambda from being triggered and -1 removes any concurrency limitations. Defaults to Unreserved Concurrency Limits -1. See Managing Concurrency

properties.name: publish
properties.description: (Optional) Whether to publish creation/change as new Lambda Function Version. Defaults to false.

properties.name: vpc_config
properties.description: (Optional) Provide this to allow your function to access your VPC. Fields documented below. See Lambda in VPC

properties.name: environment
properties.description: (Optional) The Lambda environment's configuration settings. Fields documented below.

properties.name: kms_key_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the KMS encryption key.

properties.name: source_code_hash
properties.description: (Optional) Used to trigger updates. Must be set to a base64-encoded SHA256 hash of the package file specified with either filename or s3_key. The usual way to set this is filebase64sha256("file.zip") (Terraform 0.11.12 and later) or base64sha256(file("file.zip")) (Terraform 0.11.11 and earlier), where "file.zip" is the local filename of the lambda function source archive.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the object.
dead_letter_config is a child block with a single argument:

properties.name: target_arn
properties.description: (Required) The ARN of an SNS topic or SQS queue to notify when an invocation fails. If this option is used, the function's IAM role must be granted suitable access to write to the target object, which means allowing either the sns:Publish or sqs:SendMessage action on this ARN, depending on which service is targeted.
tracing_config is a child block with a single argument:

properties.name: mode
properties.description: (Required) Can be either PassThrough or Active. If PassThrough, Lambda will only trace the request from an upstream service if it contains a tracing header with "sampled=1". If Active, Lambda will respect any tracing header it receives from an upstream service. If no tracing header is received, Lambda will call X-Ray for a tracing decision.

NOTE: if both subnet_ids and security_group_ids are empty then vpc_config is considered to be empty or unset.

properties.name: iam_roles
properties.description: (Optional) A List of ARNs for the IAM roles to associate to the Neptune Cluster.

properties.name: iam_database_authentication_enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether or mappings of AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) accounts to database accounts is enabled.

properties.name: kms_key_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the KMS encryption key. When specifying kms_key_arn, storage_encrypted needs to be set to true.

properties.name: neptune_subnet_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) A Neptune subnet group to associate with this Neptune instance.

properties.name: neptune_cluster_parameter_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) A cluster parameter group to associate with the cluster.

properties.name: preferred_backup_window
properties.description: (Optional) The daily time range during which automated backups are created if automated backups are enabled using the BackupRetentionPeriod parameter. Time in UTC. Default: A 30-minute window selected at random from an 8-hour block of time per region. e.g. 04:00-09:00

properties.name: preferred_maintenance_window
properties.description: (Optional) The weekly time range during which system maintenance can occur, in (UTC) e.g. wed:04:00-wed:04:30

properties.name: port
properties.description: (Optional) The port on which the Neptune accepts connections. Default is 8182.

properties.name: replication_source_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) ARN of a source Neptune cluster or Neptune instance if this Neptune cluster is to be created as a Read Replica.

properties.name: skip_final_snapshot
properties.description: (Optional) Determines whether a final Neptune snapshot is created before the Neptune cluster is deleted. If true is specified, no Neptune snapshot is created. If false is specified, a Neptune snapshot is created before the Neptune cluster is deleted, using the value from final_snapshot_identifier. Default is false.

properties.name: snapshot_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether or not to create this cluster from a snapshot. You can use either the name or ARN when specifying a Neptune cluster snapshot, or the ARN when specifying a Neptune snapshot.

properties.name: storage_encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the Neptune cluster is encrypted. The default is false if not specified.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the Neptune cluster.

properties.name: vpc_security_group_ids
properties.description: (Optional) List of VPC security groups to associate with the Cluster

properties.description: (Optional) Customize details about the root block device of the instance. See Block Devices below for details.

properties.name: ebs_block_device

properties.name: ephemeral_block_device
properties.description: (Optional) Customize Ephemeral (also known as "Instance Store") volumes on the instance. See Block Devices below for details.

properties.name: block-devices
properties.description: » Block devices

Each of the *_block_device attributes controls a portion of the AWS Instance's "Block Device Mapping". It's a good idea to familiarize yourself with AWS's Block Device Mapping docs to understand the implications of using these attributes.
The root_block_device mapping supports the following:

properties.name: volume_type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of volume. Can be "standard", "gp2", or "io1". (Default: "standard").

properties.name: volume_size
properties.description: (Optional) The size of the volume in gigabytes.

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of provisioned IOPS. This must be set with a volume_type of "io1".

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the volume should be destroyed on instance termination (Default: true).
Modifying any of the root_block_device settings requires resource replacement.
Each ebs_block_device supports the following:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: The name of the device to mount.

properties.name: snapshot_id
properties.description: (Optional) The Snapshot ID to mount.

properties.name: volume_type
properties.description: (Optional) The type of volume. Can be "standard", "gp2", or "io1". (Default: "standard").

properties.name: volume_size
properties.description: (Optional) The size of the volume in gigabytes.

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of provisioned IOPS. This must be set with a volume_type of "io1".

properties.name: delete_on_termination
properties.description: (Optional) Whether the volume should be destroyed on instance termination (Default: true).
Modifying any ebs_block_device currently requires resource replacement.
Each ephemeral_block_device supports the following:

properties.name: device_name
properties.description: The name of the block device to mount on the instance.

properties.name: virtual_name
properties.description: The Instance Store Device Name (e.g. "ephemeral0")

Each AWS Instance type has a different set of Instance Store block devices available for attachment. AWS publishes a list of which ephemeral devices are available on each type. The devices are always identified by the virtual_name in the format "ephemeral{0..N}".

NOTE: Currently, changes to *_block_device configuration of existing resources cannot be automatically detected by Terraform. After making updates to block device configuration, resource recreation can be manually triggered by using the taint command.

properties.description: (Required) A friendly name for the member account.

properties.name: email
properties.description: (Required) The email address of the owner to assign to the new member account. This email address must not already be associated with another AWS account.

properties.name: iam_user_access_to_billing
properties.description: (Optional) If set to ALLOW, the new account enables IAM users to access account billing information if they have the required permissions. If set to DENY, then only the root user of the new account can access account billing information.

properties.name: parent_id
properties.description: (Optional) Parent Organizational Unit ID or Root ID for the account. Defaults to the Organization default Root ID. A configuration must be present for this argument to perform drift detection.

properties.name: role_name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of an IAM role that Organizations automatically preconfigures in the new member account. This role trusts the master account, allowing users in the master account to assume the role, as permitted by the master account administrator. The role has administrator permissions in the new member account. The Organizations API provides no method for reading this information after account creation, so Terraform cannot perform drift detection on its value and will always show a difference for a configured value after import unless ignore_changes is used.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) Key-value mapping of resource tags.

properties.description: (Optional) The length of time (in seconds) that the campaign can run before it ends and message deliveries stop. This duration begins at the scheduled start time for the campaign. The minimum value is 60.

properties.name: messages_per_second
properties.description: (Optional) The number of messages that the campaign can send per second. The minimum value is 50, and the maximum is 20000.

properties.name: total
properties.description: (Optional) The maximum total number of messages that the campaign can send.

If your default authentication type fails, Amazon Pinpoint doesn't attempt to use the other authentication type.
One of the following sets of credentials is also required.

If you choose to use Certificate credentials you will have to provide: * certificate - (Required) The pem encoded TLS Certificate from Apple. * private_key - (Required) The Certificate Private Key file (ie. .key file).

If you choose to use Key credentials you will have to provide: * bundle_id - (Required) The ID assigned to your iOS app. To find this value, choose Certificates, IDs & Profiles, choose App IDs in the Identifiers section, and choose your app. * team_id - (Required) The ID assigned to your Apple developer account team. This value is provided on the Membership page. * token_key - (Required) The .p8 file that you download from your Apple developer account when you create an authentication key. * token_key_id - (Required) The ID assigned to your signing key. To find this value, choose Certificates, IDs & Profiles, and choose your key in the Keys section.

For more detailed documentation about each argument, refer to the AWS official documentation.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: allocated_storage
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier or replicate_source_db is provided) The allocated storage in gibibytes. If max_allocated_storage is configured, this argument represents the initial storage allocation and differences from the configuration will be ignored automatically when Storage Autoscaling occurs.

properties.name: allow_major_version_upgrade
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates that major version upgrades are allowed. Changing this parameter does not result in an outage and the change is asynchronously applied as soon as possible.

properties.name: apply_immediately
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether any database modifications are applied immediately, or during the next maintenance window. Default is false. See Amazon RDS Documentation for more information.

properties.name: auto_minor_version_upgrade
properties.description: (Optional) Indicates that minor engine upgrades will be applied automatically to the DB instance during the maintenance window. Defaults to true.

properties.name: availability_zone
properties.description: (Optional) The AZ for the RDS instance.

properties.name: backup_retention_period
properties.description: (Optional) The days to retain backups for. Must be between 0 and 35. Must be greater than 0 if the database is used as a source for a Read Replica. See Read Replica.

properties.name: backup_window
properties.description: (Optional) The daily time range (in UTC) during which automated backups are created if they are enabled. Example: "09:46-10:16". Must not overlap with maintenance_window.

properties.name: character_set_name
properties.description: (Optional) The character set name to use for DB encoding in Oracle instances. This can't be changed. See Oracle Character Sets Supported in Amazon RDS for more information.

properties.name: copy_tags_to_snapshot
properties.description: – (Optional, boolean) Copy all Instance tags to snapshots. Default is false.

properties.name: db_subnet_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of DB subnet group. DB instance will be created in the VPC associated with the DB subnet group. If unspecified, will be created in the default VPC, or in EC2 Classic, if available. When working with read replicas, it should be specified only if the source database specifies an instance in another AWS Region. See DBSubnetGroupName in API action CreateDBInstanceReadReplica for additional read replica contraints.

properties.name: deletion_protection
properties.description: (Optional) If the DB instance should have deletion protection enabled. The database can't be deleted when this value is set to true. The default is false.

properties.name: domain
properties.description: (Optional) The ID of the Directory Service Active Directory domain to create the instance in.

properties.name: domain_iam_role_name
properties.description: (Optional, but required if domain is provided) The name of the IAM role to be used when making API calls to the Directory Service.

properties.name: enabled_cloudwatch_logs_exports
properties.description: (Optional) List of log types to enable for exporting to CloudWatch logs. If omitted, no logs will be exported. Valid values (depending on engine): alert, audit, error, general, listener, slowquery, trace, postgresql (PostgreSQL), upgrade (PostgreSQL).

properties.name: engine
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier or replicate_source_db is provided) The database engine to use. For supported values, see the Engine parameter in API action CreateDBInstance. Note that for Amazon Aurora instances the engine must match the DB cluster's engine'. For information on the difference between the available Aurora MySQL engines see Comparison between Aurora MySQL 1 and Aurora MySQL 2 in the Amazon RDS User Guide.

properties.name: engine_version
properties.description: (Optional) The engine version to use. If auto_minor_version_upgrade is enabled, you can provide a prefix of the version such as 5.7 (for 5.7.10) and this attribute will ignore differences in the patch version automatically (e.g. 5.7.17). For supported values, see the EngineVersion parameter in API action CreateDBInstance. Note that for Amazon Aurora instances the engine version must match the DB cluster's engine version'.

properties.name: final_snapshot_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) The name of your final DB snapshot when this DB instance is deleted. If omitted, no final snapshot will be made.

properties.name: iam_database_authentication_enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether or mappings of AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) accounts to database accounts is enabled.

properties.name: identifier
properties.description:
(Optional, Forces new resource) The name of the RDS instance,
if omitted, Terraform will assign a random, unique identifier.

properties.name: identifier_prefix
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resource) Creates a unique identifier beginning with the specified prefix. Conflicts with identifier.

properties.name: instance_class
properties.description: (Required) The instance type of the RDS instance.

properties.name: iops
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of provisioned IOPS. Setting this implies a storage_type of "io1".

properties.name: kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the KMS encryption key. If creating an encrypted replica, set this to the destination KMS ARN.

properties.name: license_model
properties.description:
(Optional, but required for some DB engines, i.e. Oracle
SE1) License model information for this DB instance.

properties.name: maintenance_window
properties.description: (Optional) The window to perform maintenance in. Syntax: "ddd:hh24:mi-ddd:hh24:mi". Eg: "Mon:00:00-Mon:03:00". See RDS Maintenance Window docs for more information.

properties.name: max_allocated_storage
properties.description: (Optional) When configured, the upper limit to which Amazon RDS can automatically scale the storage of the DB instance. Configuring this will automatically ignore differences to allocated_storage. Must be greater than or equal to allocated_storage or 0 to disable Storage Autoscaling.

properties.name: monitoring_interval
properties.description: (Optional) The interval, in seconds, between points when Enhanced Monitoring metrics are collected for the DB instance. To disable collecting Enhanced Monitoring metrics, specify 0. The default is 0. Valid Values: 0, 1, 5, 10, 15, 30, 60.

properties.name: monitoring_role_arn
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the IAM role that permits RDS to send enhanced monitoring metrics to CloudWatch Logs. You can find more information on the AWS Documentation what IAM permissions are needed to allow Enhanced Monitoring for RDS Instances.

properties.name: multi_az
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies if the RDS instance is multi-AZ

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional) The name of the database to create when the DB instance is created. If this parameter is not specified, no database is created in the DB instance. Note that this does not apply for Oracle or SQL Server engines. See the AWS documentation for more details on what applies for those engines.

properties.name: option_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the DB option group to associate.

properties.name: parameter_group_name
properties.description: (Optional) Name of the DB parameter group to associate.

properties.name: password
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier or replicate_source_db is provided) Password for the master DB user. Note that this may show up in logs, and it will be stored in the state file.

properties.name: port
properties.description: (Optional) The port on which the DB accepts connections.

properties.name: publicly_accessible
properties.description: (Optional) Bool to control if instance is publicly accessible. Default is false.

properties.name: replicate_source_db
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies that this resource is a Replicate database, and to use this value as the source database. This correlates to the identifier of another Amazon RDS Database to replicate. Note that if you are creating a cross-region replica of an encrypted database you will also need to specify a kms_key_id. See DB Instance Replication and Working with PostgreSQL and MySQL Read Replicas for more information on using Replication.

properties.name: security_group_names
properties.description: (Optional/Deprecated) List of DB Security Groups to associate. Only used for DB Instances on the EC2-Classic Platform.

properties.name: skip_final_snapshot
properties.description: (Optional) Determines whether a final DB snapshot is created before the DB instance is deleted. If true is specified, no DBSnapshot is created. If false is specified, a DB snapshot is created before the DB instance is deleted, using the value from final_snapshot_identifier. Default is false.

properties.name: snapshot_identifier
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether or not to create this database from a snapshot. This correlates to the snapshot ID you'd find in the RDS console, e.g: rds:production-2015-06-26-06-05.

properties.name: storage_encrypted
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether the DB instance is encrypted. Note that if you are creating a cross-region read replica this field is ignored and you should instead declare kms_key_id with a valid ARN. The default is false if not specified.

properties.name: storage_type
properties.description: (Optional) One of "standard" (magnetic), "gp2" (general purpose SSD), or "io1" (provisioned IOPS SSD). The default is "io1" if iops is specified, "gp2" if not.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: timezone
properties.description: (Optional) Time zone of the DB instance. timezone is currently only supported by Microsoft SQL Server. The timezone can only be set on creation. See MSSQL User Guide for more information.

properties.name: username
properties.description: (Required unless a snapshot_identifier or replicate_source_db is provided) Username for the master DB user.

properties.name: vpc_security_group_ids
properties.description: (Optional) List of VPC security groups to associate.

properties.name: s3_import
properties.description: (Optional) Restore from a Percona Xtrabackup in S3. See Importing Data into an Amazon RDS MySQL DB Instance

properties.name: performance_insights_enabled
properties.description: (Optional) Specifies whether Performance Insights are enabled. Defaults to false.

properties.name: performance_insights_kms_key_id
properties.description: (Optional) The ARN for the KMS key to encrypt Performance Insights data. When specifying performance_insights_kms_key_id, performance_insights_enabled needs to be set to true. Once KMS key is set, it can never be changed.

properties.name: performance_insights_retention_period
properties.description: (Optional) The amount of time in days to retain Performance Insights data. Either 7 (7 days) or 731 (2 years). When specifying performance_insights_retention_period, performance_insights_enabled needs to be set to true. Defaults to '7'.
NOTE: Removing the replicate_source_db attribute from an existing RDS Replicate database managed by Terraform will promote the database to a fully standalone database.

properties.name: s3-import-options
properties.description: » S3 Import Options
Full details on the core parameters and impacts are in the API Docs: RestoreDBInstanceFromS3. Sample

resource "aws_db_instance" "db" {
  s3_import {
    source_engine         = "mysql"
    source_engine_version = "5.6"
    bucket_name           = "mybucket"
    bucket_prefix         = "backups"
    ingestion_role        = "arn:aws:iam::1234567890:role/role-xtrabackup-rds-restore"
  }
}

properties.name: bucket_name
properties.description: (Required) The bucket name where your backup is stored

properties.name: bucket_prefix
properties.description: (Optional) Can be blank, but is the path to your backup

properties.name: ingestion_role
properties.description: (Required) Role applied to load the data.

properties.name: source_engine
properties.description: (Required, as of Feb 2018 only 'mysql' supported) Source engine for the backup

properties.name: source_engine_version
properties.description: (Required, as of Feb 2018 only '5.6' supported) Version of the source engine used to make the backup
This will not recreate the resource if the S3 object changes in some way. It's only used to initialize the database

properties.name: timeouts
properties.description: » Timeouts
aws_db_instance provides the following Timeouts configuration options:

properties.name: create
properties.description: (Default 40 minutes) Used for Creating Instances, Replicas, and restoring from Snapshots.

properties.name: update
properties.description: (Default 80 minutes) Used for Database modifications.

properties.name: delete
properties.description: (Default 40 minutes) Used for destroying databases. This includes the time required to take snapshots.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: db_instance_identifier
properties.description: (Required) DB Instance Identifier to associate with the IAM Role.

properties.name: feature_name
properties.description: (Required) Name of the feature for association. This can be found in the AWS documentation relevant to the integration or a full list is available in the SupportedFeatureNames list returned by AWS CLI rds describe-db-engine-versions.

properties.name: role_arn
properties.description: (Required) Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM Role to associate with the DB Instance.

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Optional, Forces new resource) The name of the option group. If omitted, Terraform will assign a random, unique name. Must be lowercase, to match as it is stored in AWS.

properties.name: option_group_description

properties.name: engine_name
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the name of the engine that this option group should be associated with.

properties.name: major_engine_version
properties.description: (Required) Specifies the major version of the engine that this option group should be associated with.

properties.name: option
properties.description: (Optional) A list of Options to apply.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: option_name
properties.description: (Required) The Name of the Option (e.g. MEMCACHED).

properties.name: option_settings

properties.name: port
properties.description: (Optional) The Port number when connecting to the Option (e.g. 11211).

properties.name: version
properties.description: (Optional) The version of the option (e.g. 13.1.0.0).

properties.description: (Optional) A list of DB parameters to apply. Note that parameters may differ from a family to an other. Full list of all parameters can be discovered via aws rds describe-db-parameters after initial creation of the group.

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.
Parameter blocks support the following:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the DB parameter.

properties.name: value
properties.description: (Required) The value of the DB parameter.

properties.name: apply_method
properties.description: (Optional) "immediate" (default), or "pending-reboot". Some engines can't apply some parameters without a reboot, and you will need to specify "pending-reboot" here.
The following arguments are supported:

properties.name: name
properties.description: (Required) The name of the DB security group.

properties.name: description
properties.description: (Optional) The description of the DB security group. Defaults to "Managed by Terraform".

properties.name: ingress

properties.name: tags
properties.description: (Optional) A mapping of tags to assign to the resource.

properties.name: cidr

properties.name: security_group_name

properties.name: security_group_id

properties.name: security_group_owner_id

properties.name: db_instance_identifier

properties.name: description
